    "id": "post-2025-02-03-7292183851076898816",
    "title": "Getting my hands dirty with Deep Research right now",
    "date": "2025-02-03",
    "content": "Getting my hands dirty with Deep Research right now. Seems promising. One of my first reactions is that I love that they've carefully incorporated the clarifying questions asked into the user experience. This is a good practice if you've ever done any discovery calls or consulting work before.\"\n\"\nOf course I'm really curious about the logic of how this works. I'd assume it's probably just built into the prompt: saying something like \"ask clarifying questions\" because I've had that work pretty well in the past. \n\"\nBut the impressive general solution to this would be that the system is able to somehow explicitly, or perhaps even intuitively at some level of scale, anticipate pockets of uncertainty that might be pre-emptively addressed by simply asking the user questions that get known facts about the world and then more importantly their intentions out of their head‚Äîwhich by itself is a major value add, especially for complex problems; it's not infrequently the case that the responsible person the responsible party might not even be totally sure what their goal is, let alone explicit acceptance or success criteria from which then challenges can be derived which the agent would have to focus on when doing its work asynchronously. \n\"\nBeing able to nail this up-front in a reliable manner is going to be a huge boon for all power users of this technology, especially as the reasoning models get both more powerful and access to your private data + a broader suite of specialized tools.\n\"\n\"Highly recommend taking this for a test drive ‚Äî could be that we all just got an MBB analyst for $200/month!",
