    "id": "post-2025-01-31-7291118996362256384",
    "title": "o1 pro is just so good, oh my gosh",
    "date": "2025-01-31",
    "content": "o1 pro is just so good, oh my gosh.\"\n\"\nYou have to really think of it as an \"agent\" ‚Äî give it lots of precise instruction, lots of context. Honestly, give yourself a good 1-5 minutes to simply think and articulate the thoughts that pop out of your head via a dictation tool like Wispr Flow or superwhisper and put it into o1 Pro along with whatever other salient digital records you can spin up. \n\"\nIt's not quite as snappy as using the other models, and this violates a bit of one of my good practices that I recommend to clients: \"speed is the name of the game\" when it comes to AI experiments. 5 minutes is long enough that you can go accomplish some other task in the meantime. With that amount of time comes expectations of higher quality which you can absolutely deliver on. But that means that you really need to think through what your ask is and can you provide the system with the relevant information so it can go think about it for you.\n\"\nTo give a very concrete example, I'm giving a presentation to some highly regulated industry C-levels in a few weeks. I had set up a voice assistant via Vapi to ask them/attendees a series of discovery questions and ended up generating 6 different long-form transcripts prior to even diving in and reading the transcripts sue or not. I popped it all into o1 Pro, gave it lots of context about what it was that I was trying to do with the presentation, how I'm thinking about this strategically, and frankly a lot of details that are just not documented or at least indexed and compressed in a way that I can copy and paste. Your intentions and goals are always somewhat latent, so I've found that it's incredibly important to verbally articulate those each time you use one of these systems (this is probably the no. 2 or 3 mistake I see users make ‚Äî not clearly articulating their intent before hitting enter; this usually requires some deeper thinking by the user, but is a necessary \"literacy\" in the context of AI IMO). \n\"\nAnyway, it \"thought\" for about 4 minutes, and my goodness, am I blown away by the quality of the output here. \n\"\nWe're really moving up another level of the abstraction ladder: I didn't really have to specify a particular format or output structure that I wanted, and by not doing that, I gave it the flexibility to figure out the best way to present its findings in regard to what their top concern is and how I might be able to take the best next step in the context of what I'm trying to do. \n\"\nIt really does feel like you have a top-tier consulting firm analyst at your disposal for less than $10/day. \n\"\nCrazy stuff.\n\"\nYou just have to rethink the way that you're using these tools and optimize for quality while slowing down quite a bit at least compared to what you could do with previous model generations.\n\"\n\"Anyone else getting this kind of juice out of their Pro sub?",
