    "id": "post-2025-01-29-7290172121572421632",
    "title": "FWIW, I tried R1 (the new Chinese model from Deepseek) locally via ...",
    "date": "2025-01-29",
    "content": "FWIW, I tried R1 (the new Chinese model from Deepseek) locally via Ollama.\"\n\"\nCompared to o1 Pro, it's ... not good.\n\"\nKudos, though, to the team behind it.\n\"\nIn general, I love the OSS ethos, and downward pressure on model inference providers is good for consumers (and developers running inference at scale) ‚Äî in practice, and in my experience helping organizations adopt generative AI in a way that actually helps teams accelerate toward real-world goals, given the choice between state-of-the-art AI and anything less, if you have a complex problem you're trying to tackle, going for the hosted, best-of-breed model will make more sense. \n\"\nI don't see this changing; in fact, because the gap can close so quickly in part due to distillation (roughly, training on hosted model outputs), the Labs are actually somewhat incentived to lock down access to their best models and only deliver the value via an integrated product (Operator may be the v1 of this) that allows them to capture the kinds of profits that would justify what are essentially now pre-product looney tunes VC valuations ‚Äî that, though, may be a post for another day; there are a lot of interesting implications for entrepreneurs and enterprises when it comes to the question of whether to \"build,\" \"bolt,\" or \"buy\" the various components in the emerging AI stack.\n\"\nAll that said, DO NOT download the app and put your data into it. The servers are in China.\n\"\nInstead, download ollama and just enter \"ollama run deepseek-r1\" into your terminal.\n\"\n\"Curious to hear what others who've experience with both think...",
