    "id": "post-2025-01-26-7289272112626716673",
    "title": "We're going to be paying per-seat SaaS licenses for our agents, are...",
    "date": "2025-01-26",
    "content": "We're going to be paying per-seat SaaS licenses for our agents, aren't we...\"\n\"\nI provisioned a Google Workspace email, corporate card w/ limit, and Slack account for Operator last night so it could start submitting Upwork proposals. \n\"\nGiven that \"new employees\" is what the existing web/SaaS infrastructure is built for (and the security issues in re prompt injection, jailbreaking, etc.), it might actually make sense to just spin up general agents (basically the Labs's products) and give them premium tooling that can be used from the browser ‚Äî SaaS is the turnkey solution here, along with subscriptions to premium data sources and granular access to proprietary info (just share a doc with your agent as needed!), though I'm sure we'll see interesting and exotic solutions, too, eg, tailored MCP servers, which are kinda like software tools purpose-built for AI agents.\n\"\nI suspect that one of the more-or-less stable equilibriums we could converge on is that everyone will have their own corporation with 1‚Äì5 \"employees\" (esp. if you're starting from scratch), each one being an AI Lab's/hyperscaler's general agent product with its own memory that isn't easily shared directly with other agents.\n\"\nIf there is some degree of lock in or switching costs (there are with people because we can't directly mind meld), even if you can parallelize tasks, then we may all have companies w/ the following \"staff\":\n\"\n- Chat/Operator + SaaS licenses\n- Claude w/ MCP servers\n- Gemini (Mariner?)\n- Non-US wildcard (Chinese?)\n- Some self-hosted OSS one of these once your operation gets big enough to cover the fixed costs\n\"\nWhat the standard, AI-native corporate form, then, will look quite a bit different that the 20th c. corporation, but some of the challenges remain: information architecture and sharing, synchronization, good goal-setting, and where to invest that limited resource of attention, be it human attention or the computers' context windows...\n\"\n\"Anyone else getting hands-on with Operator? What are your thoughts?",
