    "id": "post-2025-01-24-7288567848212332545",
    "title": "The Jagged Frontier Expands ",
    "date": "2025-01-24",
    "content": "The Jagged Frontier Expands ... again.\"\n\"\nOpenAI‚Äôs first semi-autonomous web-browsing agent, Operator, launched yesterday for ChatGPT Pro users. Once again, I feel vindicated shelling out $200 a month for this package‚Äîfrankly, I‚Äôd pay more, and eventually I expect to.\n\"\nFrom my phone in bed, I‚Äôve already used Operator to:\n\"\n- Get event recommendations from GovConEvents AI (h/t Ron) by directing Operator to log into LinkedIn, grab my LinkedIn profile URL, and submit it. Operator even offered to register me automatically.\n\"\n- Create memes and post them to my bot account on Twitter using browser-based image manipulation tools.\n\"\n- Retrieve my latest Otter.ai meeting transcript entirely on its own, paste it into a new chat with Claude, and then prompt Claude to conduct a deep analysis for coaching opportunities in my role as the meeting facilitator.\n\"\nAs I try to understand what this means for my business and my clients', three main topics stand out:\n\"\n1. Security\n\"\nThese tools grow more valuable the more access they have to our data, which often means granting them persistent logins. That opens the door to potential vulnerabilities like prompt injection and jailbreaking.\n\"\nBut then again, people can be just as big an attack surface for cyber issues‚Äîthink phishing or spear phishing. New research from OpenAI suggests that as system-two reasoning models get better, they might become more resilient to adversarial attacks. I do know, however, that the average human worker is not very resilient. Make of that what you will.\n\"\n2. Necessarily Evolving Norms (Especially in the Enterprise)\n\"\nAs I‚Äôve written before, centralized IT is simply not a good fit for a world where AI capabilities evolve at such a rapid pace. Centralized IT often becomes a bottleneck, preventing employees‚Äîand therefore the organization‚Äîfrom realizing the full benefits of these tools.\n\"\nIf enterprises don‚Äôt proactively decentralize IT functions, top-tier talent (made 10x or 100x more productive by state-of-the-art AI products like Operator) will leave. That‚Äôs something that should keep CEOs up at night.\n\"\n3. Ethan Mollick's \"Jagged Frontier\n\"\nAI succeeds and fails in surprising ways; humans and AI each hold comparative advantages depending on the context and tasks at hand. Practically:\n\"\n- Unbundle roles. A traditional role is really a bundle of tasks, so break it down.\n\"\n- Delegate to AI. Offload the tasks where AI has a clear edge.\n\"\n- Re-bundle human roles so they handle everything else with maximal impact.\n\"\nIf humans are now only needed for (say) 10% of tasks in a 20th-century knowledge worker role‚Äîbut they can do that 10% ten times more effectively when paired with advanced AI‚Äîthen the overall value and scope of responsibility for each knowledge worker skyrockets.\n\"\nWhat next?\n\"\nGet hands-on with Operator yourself. \n\"\nDiscover via experimentation what was impossible yesterday that‚Äôs now possible, and then figure out how to use those new capabilities to make your customers 10x better off.\n\"\n\"Good luck!",
