    "id": "post-2025-01-11-7283839961680777216",
    "title": "asi futures and the importance of 'Œµ' ",
    "date": "2025-01-11",
    "content": "asi futures and the importance of 'Œµ' ...\"\n\"\nWhat the heck is the future of work going to look like, not simply in the context of machines that perform incremental reading, writing, and reasoning tasks, but in the context of increasingly capable models bundled with other components (action through eg computer use and long term memory) into self-propagating swarms of \"agents\" moving toward a higher-order goal?\n\"\nI'm definitely sympathetic to one line of thinking, where these swarms overwhelm and transform traditional industries (in no small part because it's kinda sci fi and fun to imagine) ‚Äî but, suspect that the frontier of what ai can do, even when working semi-autonomously in a productive OODA loop, will continue to be quite varied, even as the scope of what can be computed explodes (see: Ethan Mollick's \"jagged frontier\" or the discussion in re \"spiky models,\" especially since the o-series have come online).\n\"\nThere's a meaningful difference, then, between:\n\"\n1. a future where human capability is a subset of superintelligent machine capability (this is the charismatic sci-fi scenario where ubi sort of makes sense) and\n\"\n2. there's greater and greater Venn diagram overlap (though dwarfed by the expansion of the asi circle into problem spaces we as humans can't properly access, at least without some social or coordination technology) BUT always some gap or error term or Œµ that's nicely fitted to a human person.\n\"\nMy hunch (and hope) is that it's 2, in which case we should see those Œµ values aggregate into new roles that are highly complementary to ai capability, pretty alien compared to 20th c white collar roles, and probably extremely lucrative if they truly do bundle tasks that are economically complementary to machine outputs.\n\"\nWhat might those new roles be?\n\"\nIdk for sure, but here are a few guesses:\n\"\n- artisanal cybernetician\n- swarm orchestrator\n- context steward\n- trust & reputation banker\n- corporate contemplative\n\"\nWhat other new jobs might emerge in the age of intelligent machines?\n\"\nLmk in the comments...\n\"\n\"(ported from an exchange w Marc Lien on another platform - do give him a follow on LinkedIn as well!)",
