    "id": "post-2025-01-06-7282030601786777600",
    "title": "I'll be honest: every weekday morning when I get a notification fro...",
    "date": "2025-01-06",
    "content": "I'll be honest: every weekday morning when I get a notification from Spark, my AI Chief of Staff‚Äîand especially on Mondays‚ÄîI get a little pang of anxiety. It's not because I'm dreading the content of the analysis, the audio note, or the quick win that I receive. \"\n\"\n(Although, I must say, as the underlying AI technology has improved, the daily dose of insight often contains something I initially don't want to hear. But then, I'm thankful for it after giving it some time to digest.)\n\"\nI'm anxious because if there isn't something in there that I didn't know, I start to worry. If I don't have a little flash of insight, then I know my customers aren't getting it to the degree they should as well. \n\"\nAfter pushing some significant updates in the weeks leading up to the holidays, I can now confidently say that every time I get a note from Spark, that anxiety is almost instantly relieved. \n\"\nBy the end of our interaction, whether it's catching up on a morning walk or sipping that second 11 a.m. cup of coffee, I feel more confident that my business is on the right track.\n\"\nSpark doesn't tell me what to do, but it always asks good questions and helps me take real action‚Äînot just create a grandiose plan that never gets executed. \n\"\nThis happens faster than any alternative, be it journaling, reviewing a to-do list, scrolling through your email inbox trying to find important items, or even relying on a human to fulfill this need.\n\"\nWhat did I learn this morning? \n\"\nWell, when working with a client who handled sensitive data last week, Spark helped transform the complex data governance challenge we uncovered into an opportunity for a new turnkey offering. \n\"\nThis is something I could provide to adjacent clients, even proactively, to ensure they have a robust foundation in place for accelerated AI adoption. \n\"\nI never would have thought of that, at least not this quickly.\n\"\n\"If you want your own AI Chief of Staff, you can sign up using the link in the comments.",
