    "id": "post-2025-01-05-7281684925844488192",
    "title": "There's a ripe mid-market frontier opening up, and it's yours for t...",
    "date": "2025-01-05",
    "content": "There's a ripe mid-market frontier opening up, and it's yours for the taking...\"\n\"\nIt used to be that minimum spend to get a software product up-and-running was maybe $10ks per month (development or growth specialist labor, respectively, which can be comp'd in cash or equity of course, but is substantial either way); now you can do it for hundreds or low thousands by \"hiring,\" e.g., o1 Pro, to catalyze:\n\"\nProduct dev: articulate your expertise through the spoken word and iterate with Chat until you have a working product, shipped via one-click deploy on @Replit, you can send someone, and they can get value from. \n\"\nIf you're already an expert in meeting some particular set of needs, the best way to bootstrap this is to ask, \"What would I do for existing clients if I could clone myself?\" (For me, the answer is deliver daily insight, as a complement to the weekly insight I help teams generate through my c-level management process [link to my product in the replies if curious].)\n\"\nIterate with early customers quickly and skillfully, e.g., by instrumenting your product with Posthog and Sentry (makes easier to be proactive and responsive, respectively, recording bi-weekly feedback interviews, and piping your code + the transcript back into o1 Pro: Identify one change you can make in, let's say, an hour or less, and ship it!\n\"\nKeep doing this until at least one of your early customers confirms that they'd be in screaming pain if you took the product away from them; at that point, when they're elated because of some salient, surprising benefit, simply ask, \"Who's one person you know needs this?\n\"\n(First time I did this, the customer said he'd \"burn down my house down\" if I pulled his access; that's the level of potency you want to aim for.)\n\"\nMake it easy for them to make a referral with a succinct Alex Iskold‚Äìstyle forward-able email, and you'll get to 10 customers in no time. (Literally every time I've done this, I closed on the first call. Those authentic, energized referrals are worth a lot, and what's great is you don't have to implement some complicated sales process ‚Äî you literally just have to make your customers happy by making something they love (or \"loves them\" in the medieval sense).\n\"\nGrowth: complement these referrals with high-quality posting. I hated even the thought of posting on social maybe 3 years ago, but got over it with a combination of reps and approaching it with a mindset of \"I'm only going to post if it energizes me; I don't care what people think.\" \n\"\nThe key here is generating raw material to meditate on in the first place. You do this via the development process I described earlier (or, as an antecedent, consulting engagements where you cultivate expertise that you can bake into a product ‚Äî took me ~18 months to take my consulting rate from $85 to $1000 / hr, and I may post about that process in the future...); solving others' problems in private makes for great discoveries to yap about in public...\n\"\n\"(Pt. 2 linked in comments...)",
    "excerpt": "There's a ripe mid-market frontier opening up, and it's yours for the taking...\" \"\" \"It used to be that minimum spend to get a software product up-and-running...",
