    "id": "post-2025-01-03-7281026774069592064",
    "title": "I‚Äôve been thinking a lot about how to create a truly externally-fac...",
    "date": "2025-01-03",
    "content": "I‚Äôve been thinking a lot about how to create a truly externally-facing AI presence that doesn‚Äôt just imitate old-school methods. There are basically three approaches I‚Äôve seen so far:\"\n\"\n1.\tWebsite Chatbots\n\"\nYou can drop a chatbot on your homepage‚Äîbut, it never quite feels right. Most of the time, it‚Äôs just an annoying pop-up that interrupts a user who‚Äôs trying to read or navigate.\n\"\n2.\tClones\n\"\nYou build an AI persona that's a stand-in for ‚Äúyou,‚Äù fielding inbound questions at scale. It can handle repetitive FAQs, but unless you have a massive audience, it's hard to justify the UX tradeoff: the models aren't quite there when it comes to getting your \"vibe\" across, and while that gap will close as the core tech gets better, there may end up being a pretty deep uncanny valley.\n\"\n3.\tA New Way? (Outbound & Helpful)\n\"\nInstead of automating your voice to trick people into thinking they‚Äôre talking to a human (the worst of this being pseudo-personalized email & LinkedIn spam), why not design an AI persona from scratch‚Äîsomething that transparently shows up as a helpful assistant when folks post about the very topics you‚Äôre great at?\n\"\nThis ‚Äúthird way‚Äù is about a new kind of relationship-building:\n\"\n\t‚Ä¢\tThe AI assistant engages in a right-sized, context-aware way.\n\t‚Ä¢\tIt‚Äôs clearly labeled as a bot, so no one feels duped.\n\t‚Ä¢\tIt offers real value‚Äîmaybe asks a clarifying question or shares a relevant tip‚Äîjust enough to build a modicum of trust.\n\"\nThe hope is that people see this AI persona, realize it‚Äôs genuinely helpful, and then decide to learn more about what you (and your product or service) can do. It‚Äôs a fresh approach that avoids the spammy ‚Äúcarnival barker‚Äù vibe & allows you to scale your know-how a bit by taking you out of the loop (key insight here: instant replies to posts have EXTREMELY high response rates; being able to close the loop in a few seconds rather than a few hours, let alone a few days is produces qualitatively different results, and this is only really possible if you delegate some small action to intelligent, discursive, semi-autonomous media).\n\"\nI‚Äôm actually spinning up this concept for Powerline‚Äôs ‚ÄúSpark‚Äù‚Äîthe remote team CEO's AI chief-of-staff. It‚Äôll go out on Twitter in the near future, interact thoughtfully with people who seem to need a little help, and (hopefully) nurture those relationships in a way that‚Äôs both human-friendly and scalable.\n\"\nAll of this goes back to my core belief in quality over quantity‚Äînot churning out more meaningless content, AKA \"LLM slop,\" or ‚Äúfaking it‚Äù online, but reimagining how AI can genuinely enhance conversations. I‚Äôll report back on the results once it‚Äôs live.\n\"\nMark Amtower, thanks again for the lively discussion that got this out of my head...\n\"\n\"(If you‚Äôre curious, I‚Äôll drop a link in the comments to some of the discussion that sparked this idea!)",
