    "id": "post-2024-12-17-7274817181140369408",
    "title": "Claude is such a great thought partner ‚Äî I've been grappling with t...",
    "date": "2024-12-17",
    "content": "Claude is such a great thought partner ‚Äî I've been grappling with the problems of applied AI + adoption, and then the deeper issue of organizational reformation, for years now, and piped a lot of my long-form content + coffee-fueled thoughts this morning into 3.5 Sonnet (prompted to be a little extra disagreeable).\"\n\"\nSome key takeaways, worth meditating on, I think, for anyone serious about integration (these are complex, gnarly, but ultimately addressable set of challenges!):\n\"\n- identifying durable expertise and the tacit or embodied knowledge (in both \"single-player\" and \"multi-player\" modes) is super, super important;\n\"\n- using digital media (e.g., private Slack groups w/ weekly recorded \"AI show-and-tell\" sessions that invite shadow IT superusers to step into the limelight and passively document what they've learned) as a means of cultural continuity;\n\"\n- liquid, global, fractional, async labor market participation (when to work with Upworkers, specialist shops, individual SMEs, software INSTEAD of services? Which tasks or projects do you delegate, and how do you tailor the engagements, and especially compensation, accordingly?);\n\"\n- who exactly are those 1‚Äì5% of individuals in your organization who can be invited to form the core cross-functional team that moves the entire thing forward post-transformation? (My guess is that they can come from any \"level\" as the corporate forms of the future may come to resemble more fluid networks vs. rigid hierarchies)\n\"\nThe key takeaway?\n\"\nYou need to run experiments to find out!\n\"\n\"Arm your people with the tools, point them toward good goals, and embrace change‚Äîas you venture out on the frontier and discover exactly those things that are possible that were literally impossible a few months ago, the answers to these questions will become more clear...",
