    "id": "post-2024-11-25-7266890210452418560",
    "title": "Struggling to decide which AI to use for a creative writing task?\"\n...",
    "date": "2024-11-25",
    "content": "Struggling to decide which AI to use for a creative writing task?\"\n\"\nClaude or ChatGPT or...both?!\n\"\nClaude (Sonnet 3.5) is better for writing prose, but OpenAI's o1 model is better at writing specs for Sonnet...\n\"\nHere's how it works - I did this with a client a couple of weeks ago:\n\"\n1. interviewed him live about a topic he's an expert in\n2. captured his answers in a live Otter transcript\n3. piped that into o1 w/ a prompt to write a spec for another copywriter (and provided context in re target audience and overarching goals)\n4. took the spec that o1 outputted along with the raw transcript and piped all that into Claude\n5. iterated live w/ the client, capturing their live feedback and Otter\n6. few rounds of copy/paste feedback <> Claude chat to get the copy 95% the way there\n7. client made a couple tweaks and posted to LinkedIn\n\"\nAdding o1 in the middle to do some more strategic thinking boosts the quality of the core content, while Sonnet compresses it all in an aesthetically pleasing way.\n\"\nThis illustrates a broader general lesson ‚Äî when it comes to getting the most out of an applied AI exercise, three things are always true:\n\"\n1. Talk, don't type.\n2. More is more (data and models).\n3. Speed is the name of the game ‚Äî go fast, and don't give up until you've satisfied pre-specified acceptance criteria!\n\"\nIt's literally possible to use AI to GSD 10x faster.\n\"\n\"Now, go get a widescreen monitor, switch to dictation over typing, open a few browser tabs, set an ambitious goal, and give yourself 1/10th the time you normally take...",
