    "title": "The art of \"building product\" is changing, radically",
    "date": "2024-11-21",
    "content": "The art of \"building product\" is changing, radically.\"\n\"\nThis morning, I had a customer feedback call...\n\"\nAnd not 5 minutes after it ended, I piped the Fireflies.ai transcript and my server codebase, hosted on Replit, into OpenAI's o1-preview (w/ some docs for a relevant API-based service) and asked it to make changes to implement a particular feature he requested.\n\"\nWhile o1 was \"thinking,\" in parallel, I started a 3.5 Sonnet chat in Anthropic's Claude w/ that same transcript + my product homepage HTML; I asked for updates to the marketing copy per his feedback...\n\"\nA few rounds of \"cmd+a, cmd+c, cmd+v\" later‚Äîand within 20 minutes of our call ending‚ÄîI was able to push these updates to production (love Replit's 1-click deploy feature!) that improved both the core functionality & marketability of the product.\n\"\nTHIS is how you develop software (or do any kind of knowledge work, really) w/ AI ‚Äî SPEED is the name of the game.\n\"\nNo \"scrum rituals,\" no \"backlog grooming,\" no \"managing stakeholders\"*...\n\"\nJust iterating toward product‚Äìmarket fit at the speed of thought.\n\"\n*As I've written about previously, AI is less interesting as an information technology per se (though, clearly, when it comes to unsticking proprietary knowledge‚Äîboth \"know-how\" and \"know-that\"‚Äîand encoding it into a capital asset, it ain't bad); what's more interesting are the \"social technologies\" it unlocks, and that means radical reformation for organizations, small and large.\n\"\n\"Leaders who want their institutions to thrive in the 21st century shouldn't be content with marginal gains from AI adoption ‚Äî you should expect step-change improvements, a consequence of serious business process reengineering, and transformational change (enabled by top-down political will and bottoms-up user-led innovation) as the fundamental ways in which work get done evolve, and so do the shapes of the teams and individual roles that GSD at speeds that were unthinkable in a pre-AI world.",
