    "title": "I don't do didactic presentations on AI anymore",
    "date": "2024-11-21",
    "content": "I don't do didactic presentations on AI anymore. \"\n\"\nAnd if you're serious about adopting the tech, you shouldn't attend them ‚Äî or, TBH, watch YouTube videos, purchase courses, etc., EXCEPT...\n\"\n...if it's in the context of you having already committed to producing something with the tools, something ambitious and under extreme time contraints that you literally could not have without AI.\n\"\nWhy not? \n\"\nPeople love webinars, presentations, podcast interviews, etc...and they're willing to shell out cash for them, especially at the corporate level!\n\"\nBecause it's not aligned with the actual objective of any of these exercises: to help people retool, either in the context of the organization they're currently a part of, or as they seek new opportunities and prepare to reenter this new 21st-century economy.\n\"\nPassive consumption of charismatic media gives you the false sense of progress ‚Äî that you learned something that makes you feel a bit smarter, that you can pass along to colleagues to demonstrate your AI-savviness, that this \"AI thing\" is now a bit more within your control, and you're going to \"be ok\" (e.g., keep your job).\n\"\nUnfortunately, that feeling you get has very little to do with whether or not you're actually retooling. Passive consumption‚Äîor even meditating on the core content, even if it's high-quality‚Äîis not enough!\n\"\nYou have to actually do things! You need to TAKE ACTION!\n\"\n(And, especially at the beginning, it can be excruciatingly uncomfortable, especially if you're coming in with limiting beliefs like, \"I can't code!\")\n\"\nRemember, there are no experts in AI, only pioneers, and the dynamic nature of the technology is such that real gains can only be achieved through rapid experimentation in a domain that you find energizing and, if sufficiently navigated / ordered with the help of this technology, would lead to better outcomes for the customers and colleagues who benefit from your hard work.\n\"\nEspecially at the beginning of the retooling journey, much of the investment of energy and attention goes into \"muddling through\" the process of making something (again that was impossible to do given the same constraints) good; general principles, good practices, etc. emerge from that process, and some awareness of them prior may be helpful, but it's much better to learn in the course of a real project with acceptance criteria than devouring didactic media on its own.\n\"\nSo, if you're tempted to:\n\"\n- sign up for more newsletters,\n- watch YouTube tutorials,\n- scroll through X for the latest AI goss,\n- pay consultants for $X00,000 slideware,\n- hire an \"AI expert\" to do standardized company-wide training or seminars...\n\"\n...DON'T!\n\"\n\"Instead, scope a good goal, muster the energy to suffer through the process of clicking and typing and changing core habits until you've made something that a dispassionate third-party has verified is actually GOOD; only then will you gain the the tacit knowledge that makes it 10x easier to tackle the next task with AI.",
