    "title": "Super interesting ‚Äî¬†when confidence is high (something is \"known\"),...",
    "date": "2024-10-31",
    "content": "Super interesting ‚Äî¬†when confidence is high (something is \"known\"), LLMs are like retrieval engines that index and compress relevant facts (\"know-that\") or process knowledge (\"know-how\").\"\n\"\nWhen it's low, they're more like hypothesis generators, which you can take as an invitation to take action to reduce uncertainty and therefore gain an information edge.\n\"\n\"Would be quite powerful to be able to know which \"mode\" the system is in (probably a function of the logit variance?) when you're tackling a problem: and, on top of that, the difference between confidence given your own data asset (e.g., relevant tokens pulled in for ICL) and the underlying foundation model's \"common knowledge\" ‚Äî¬†that should be the basis of the relative value and potential profitability of what you know that no-one else does...",
