    "id": "post-2024-10-29-7257088529028059136",
    "title": "I am incredibly honored to have been a part of making year's MIT AI...",
    "date": "2024-10-29",
    "content": "I am incredibly honored to have been a part of making year's MIT AI Conference happen for the first time in New York. \"\n\"\nIt was a joy working with the volunteer team to make this a reality over the past year.\n\"\nOur goal was to put on AI conference that's a little different from what you'd find elsewhere: In particular, there's a lot of charismatic speculation at the moment, both utopian and dystopian, about what might be coming down the pipeline due to AI. \n\"\nWhile I do love thinking about the future, we thought it was important to construct programs around sharing fresh, surprising, and practical insights with attendees‚Äîinsights based on real data generated by AI pioneers across industries who have been integrating the technology into production workflows. \n\"\nI'm happy to say that we accomplished our objective.\n\"\nThat raises the question of what I found most practically insightful from the conference. I have to say it was the common thread across multiple technical founders from various industries, who, for the first in many years in some cases, were rolling up their sleeves again and writing code at speeds previously thought impossible (thanks to new models like O1 from OpenAI).\n\"\nThis experience gave me continued enthusiasm and motivation this week to keep working on a product I've been building in stealth for CEOs‚Äîa project that's, for now, essentially going from zero to one on my own (w/ some help from Chat and Claude).\n\"\nBroadly, the general takeaway is that for anybody who's been away from the front lines‚Äîwhether you climbed the ranks in a technical organization, sales, or any other modern corporate function‚Äîthere's no better time than the present to get your hands dirty again.\n\"\nLearning how to apply this technology to solve problems deep in the weeds is crucial. You'll be shocked to discover that some things work far better than expected, while the technology fails in surprising ways as well. \n\"\nBy doing this, you'll be able to confidently implement company-wide policies and make sound strategic decisions about what AI will mean for your organization.\n\"\nGodspeed! and I look forward to seeing everyone in 2025 back in California for next year's conference. \n\"\nSpecial thanks to the volunteer team, our sponsors, and our speakers who made this year's event a resounding success.\n\"\n\"cc Shuja Keen Anvisha Pai Dima Ayyash Rebeca Eun Young Hwang Stacy Yu Mainak Ghosh Daniela Gorza, thank you for going above and beyond, leading the entire volunteer team (all of whom I'd tag here were it not for LinkedIn's tagging limits!) to an excellent outcome ‚Äî now, onto the next one :)",
