    "id": "post-2024-10-28-7256704147763204096",
    "title": "AI as \"suprasocial media\" & what happens when we collectively stop ...",
    "date": "2024-10-28",
    "content": "AI as \"suprasocial media\" & what happens when we collectively stop typing and start talking...\"\n\"\nThere's been some interesting discussion about the accuracy and reliability of AI scribes for doctors (in particular, that there are discrepancies between the doctor or patient's recollection of the visit and what's contained in the machine-generated notes), and that, I think, begs the question of, \"Is rote note-taking even the correct application of this technology in this scenario?\" \n\"\nIt's become clear to me that AI is actually a \"discursive\" medium (vs. a broadcast one), and IMO, instead of simply translating a raw recording into EHR-compatible text, the computer should first ask the doctor tough questions post‚Äìpatient encounter. \n\"\nOne could make the argument that writing itself is just a simulation of discourse (a less expensive and more accessible technology than the thing you really want, which is a competent and contextually aware thought partner) because you're externalizing your thoughts and interacting with them as they're transmitted back to you visually.\n\"\nAs Moore's Law moves us closer to resolving Moravec's Paradox (LLMs / GPUs are actually something like the neuronal structures in our \"gut,\" a step below hyper-rational CPU-enabled deductive reasoning), we should expect a shift to oral/discursive communication (and, then, maybe that's supplanted something like vibe-based embodied interaction as spatial and ambient computing technologies mature and eventually dovetail); given the global scale and speed-of-light distribution of information IT enables, the key difference between how our ancestors used those kinds of media and our experience with this new twist on something ancient will be the suprasocial nature of it all: When you interact with an AI, who/what is on the other end? \n\"\nIt's not a person, but it's not quite a tool either.\n\"\nOne of the first things I always recommend to clients when they start learning how to use AI to GSD is that they, \"stop typing and start talking.\" It's a tough habit to break, but once you do, the scope of what you can do with computers explodes, since you can more directly input your thoughts into a computer.\n\"\nBut, as we come to rely on AI-mediated experiences (again, as opposed to the 1:1 display of your unprocessed thoughts reflected to you via word processor), those outputs will be shaped by increasingly incomprehensibly complex (and evolving!) processes, like single cells receiving signals from a CNS.\n\"\n\"All this is to say that, practically, it's becoming more important than ever to unplug periodically. Technology is good; AI is good. But, don't forget to take the exocortex off periodically and \"think naked.\" Otherwise, you may find yourself conforming to the system, rather than participating in it.",
