    "title": "If:\"\n\"\"\n\"1",
    "date": "2024-10-23",
    "content": "If:\"\n\"\n1. relatively rote reading and writing tasks (and now some more complex reasoning tasks, as seems to be the case with the new test-time compute paradigm illustrated by OpenAI's o1-preview model) can be done quickly and cheaply by computers and \n\"\n2. From a cybersecurity perspective, each additional knowledge worker with privileged access to information systems could increase the surface area that attackers can target, potentially posing a liability, then\n\"\nWhat are the circumstances in which it makes sense not only to bring on a contractor for time-bound, outcome-specific specialist work but to actually hire a full-time employee? \n\"\nThe calculus surrounding these decisions is, or at least should be, evolving in light of advancements in AI. \n\"\nI have some hunches, but I'm curious about what others think...\n\"\n\"(This question spurred by rather juicy nugget from The Information about one of the AI labs considering changing their own SWE hiring plans because of the productivity boost afforded to current workers by the latest generation of their own tech; h/t @aidan_mclau on x.)",
