    "id": "post-2024-10-22-7254500272062783488",
    "title": "Some fun speculation in re where AI is taking professional communic...",
    "date": "2024-10-22",
    "content": "Some fun speculation in re where AI is taking professional communication and what it means for you...\"\n\"\n(Spurred by the Twitter thread in the ss.)\n\"\nIf we've communicated 1:1 digitally, you know I love voice notes üòÖ (and Loom videos).\n\"\nI think it's good practice that high-fidelity multimedia messages; eg audio notes, Loom videos; are accompanied by a transcript and summarized version (you can do this manually, and I have been, in general, for the past ~2 years) ‚Äî Slack does a good job already with the former and Apple seems to be doing a good job w/ the latter.\n\"\nRaw audio/video broadcasts without summaries put a burden on the recipient; but, thanks to AI, it's trivial to distill the core information to its essence (and personalize it).\n\"\nIn fact, on the receiving end, you can pop the transcript into a tool like Claude and explore the core content according to your needs, as if you had an intelligent scribe mediating the information on your behalf, thereby protecting your attention (and even surfacing the items between the lines that most deserve it, especially thanks to the simulated reasoning capabilities of new models, eg, o1 from OpenAI).\n\"\nThis trend in the limit, of course, is human speech (and other contextually relevant digital exhaust)->AI<->AI->compressed multimedia->human.\n\"\nAnd that means that your expectations in re quality for live interactions eg meetings should be astronomically high ‚Äî starting today!\n\"\n\"Meetings as a means of rote information transmission are the fax machines of the 21st-century corporation ‚Äî anything but the most engaging, complex, and unresolved items should be delegated to computers or humans via computers :)",
