    "id": "post-2024-10-15-7252007805300154368",
    "title": "RTO mandates will knee-cap organizations",
    "date": "2024-10-15",
    "content": "RTO mandates will knee-cap organizations. \"\n\"\nGoing \"AI-native\" necessitates ongoing generation of high-quality data: not just work product, but a high-fidelity account of processes.\n\"\nThat data is easier to generate through remote, asynchronous interactions.\n\"\nThat said, there may be situations in which actively choosing not to digitize something in a professional context (in the interest, say, of extending the \"shelf life\" of a secret) make sense; but, those will become fewer and further between as the compounding benefits of information liquidity in a high-trust, AI-mediated organization overwhelm the marginal benefits of information compartmentalization and secret hoarding.\n\"\nWhat's most interesting to me about AI is not the technology per se (at least in \"single-player\" mode), but the social technologies it unlocks in \"multiplayer mode\" ‚Äî the dynamic shapes of these new types of lean, liquid, and hyper-differentiated organizations that couldn't exist in a pre-AI, pre-internet world of high transaction costs.\n\"\nIf you're paying attention, you can catch glimpses of the post-Coasean (trans-Coasean?) firm in the indie hacker world, some VC-backed startups, market networks like Replit, and crypto DAOs.\n\"\nAs you think about how to lead (and manage) through the AI transformation, I'd invite you to resist the urge to cling to the office, meetings as means of rote information transmission, full-time employment, and all other trappings of the 20th-century corporation‚Äîand instead, first, meditate on how knowledge workers might collaborate and coordinate in a world where the costs of reading and writing the marginal word approach zero.\n\"\n\"The upside for existing institutions with the preexisting cornered resources of capital, trust, and knowledge is enormous if decision-makers are willing to consider new things in a new way and, thus, be led (and not dragged) into the 21st century.",
