    "id": "post-2024-09-19-7242562562528088064",
    "title": "I've been trying to think through what exactly constitutes a \"data ...",
    "date": "2024-09-19",
    "content": "I've been trying to think through what exactly constitutes a \"data asset,\" the economic complement to AI your business continuously generates, cultivates, and capitalizes upon...\"\n\"\nAnd after doing some noodling this morning, it occurred to me that \"cornered resources\" (in the Hamilton Helmer 7 Powers sense) have roughly the following schema in the AI age ‚Äî¬†they can be digitized and indexed in such a way that they're made more useful as the foundation models become more capable:\n\"\n- rare records (\"know-that,\" especially that which obviates limiting beliefs and unlocks opportunities to obliterate, rather than simply automate, existing processes),\n\"\n- novel methods (\"know-how,\" which can be increasingly encoded in software as tacit knowledge becomes legible to multimodal models that can \"unstick\" information from raw process recordings), and\n\"\n- trust (\"know-who,\" which is at least a model of the formal interpersonal structure within a larger organization, and, at best, meaningful relationships with those same folks)\n\"\nNow, how this gets captured, modeled, and mined is an entirely different question, and one I'll be continuing to investigate ‚Äî¬†although I have some strong early indications that the way this worked in the past (e.g., via relational databases and traditional CRMs) will be very different than what the \"AI-native\" architecture looks like going forward ... more to come :)\n\"\n[this is just 1 of 5 takeaways (each w/ an actionable insight) from my great \"private podcast\" convo w/ Stewart Alsop this am ‚Äî¬†we do these bi-monthly, and they've been indispensable as I've tried to continue making sense of what I'm encountering helping clients apply AI to solve their problems faster + integrate the tech into org's at lots of different levels of size & scope...]\n\"\nHe's a great interviewer! \n\"\n\"Would highly recommend dm'ing Stewart if you could use some help periodically updating your / your business's longer-term view w/ a helpful thought partner...",
