    "id": "post-2024-09-17-7241908233752182785",
    "title": "Sounds a bit silly, but getting good at leveraging the general purp...",
    "date": "2024-09-17",
    "content": "Sounds a bit silly, but getting good at leveraging the general purpose AI tools, which are constantly in flux, feels a bit more like becoming a sommelier than, say, an engineer (I am neither, so take that with a grain of salt).\"\n\"\nFor example, this morning, I carved out my first deep work session in quite a while to build a prototype (that I hope is the seed of something that fundamentally change how corporations work ü§û‚Äî I'm happy to say early results are so far, so good).\n\"\nAny, I opened Cursor, Claude Pro, Figma, and Chat, and then started off by giving both o1 (OpenAI's new reasoning model) and Anthropic's 3.5 Sonnet the same giant prompt (my long-form spoken articulation via superwhisper of the problem / potential solution + 4x brute-forced copied-and-pasted API services' docs).\n\"\nAfter a minute or so, they both came up with boilerplate.\n\"\nI popped Sonnet's into o1's and asked it to combine the best of both, which it did.\n\"\nOnce o1 hit a wall, I went back to Sonnet.\n\"\nThere are clearly some parts of the \"jagged frontier\" of latent space where different models have differentiated advantages; the only way you can get a feel for them (and, IMO it really is a feel, not something you can easily quantify with, e.g., benchmarks) is to furiously and continuously experiment, even with an ensemble working on the same problem that necessitates lengths of word-crunching, then some quantitative analysis, then maybe some coding, etc.\n\"\n\"It's all very dynamic, hard to measure (which is why it's critical you get clear on the desired outcome and timebox your AI-enhanced sprints), and practically \"vibe-based\" ‚Äî not unlike managing a cross-functional team!",
