    "id": "post-2024-09-17-7241896912948273153",
    "title": "10 things I've come to believe over the past year:\"\n\"\"\n\"1",
    "date": "2024-09-17",
    "content": "10 things I've come to believe over the past year:\"\n\"\n1. AI will enable a new era of remote, asynchronous, fractional work by lowering barriers of space, time, language and culture. This will accelerate the emergence of global liquid labor markets.\n\"\n2. The most valuable data will come from solving real problems for people at the frontiers of fields. Digitizing both the process and results will allow this data to be leveraged as a complement to increasingly commoditized AI. \n\"\n3. AI's main value is as a compressor and filter - it allows the most important unresolved items to quickly be surfaced so humans can focus their limited attention on what matters most. The key is providing it high-quality, salient data.\n\"\n4. Voice will become the dominant interface for personal computing as AI capabilities grow. This will necessitate rethinking home and office environments to provide privacy for talking to computers.\n\"\n5. Trust is the most important factor for productivity. AI may help build trust at scale by facilitating rich asynchronous interactions and surfacing the most relevant information.\n\"\n6. Corporations will need to fundamentally re-architect themselves around AI, becoming leaner and more muscular. Standard employer-employee relationships will evolve as more tacit knowledge can be digitized.\n\"\n7. The ceiling on individual productivity is rising faster than the floor due to AI. Power users leveraging the tools in sophisticated ways will see exponential gains.\n\"\n8. Curiosity, humility and a focus on doing what energizes you are key to thriving in an AI-powered economy. The goal is reducing uncertainty on the path to ambitious goals.\n\"\n9. We're still very early in the AI transformation, comparable to the early days of electrification. The full implications will take decades to play out but will be profound.\n\"\n10. AI can enhance critical thinking by probing human reasoning with incisive questions. The aim is elevating quality of thought, not delegating thinking to machines.\n\"\n\"Special thanks to Claude for helping me compress all of my posts since '23 into just one :)",
