    "title": "This is 100% true",
    "date": "2024-09-09",
    "content": "This is 100% true. One of the challenges that C-level decision makers face at the moment is that they have a lot of different, seemingly credible people making pretty bold assertions in both positive and negative directions about AI and what they should do about it. \"\n\"\nBut few of them have much direct experience with the technology. And for reasons that make sense.\n\"\nMost of the people who've gotten really good at using generative AI over the past year or so have done so, yes, because of interest, but also because of constraints. \n\"\nIf you're a bootstrapped startup founder and wanna accelerate the rate at which you get stuff done, it has made much more sense over the past year, especially as the models have gotten more powerful to quote, \"hire\", unquote, a computer or application like Claude to help do bits and pieces of work versus hiring a person to take on a bundle of tasks. \n\"\nIf you're a C-level executive at an enterprise, you likely have already hired excellent people to do different jobs. And so that constraint isn't quite there in the same way. \n\"\nThe way the best path forward for executives who wanna learn is to identify those clerical and administrative reading and writing tasks that they would like done sooner and may have already created a habit of delegating to people but don't wanna wait. \n\"\nIn particular, summarizing long documents and then using AI as a thought partner to analyze them or mulling through raw recordings of customer interactions with an AI intermediary versus waiting for interpretations from managers. \n\"\n\"Once the tools become more deeply integrated into your workflow, the big strategic questions in regard to what to do about them become significantly easier to answer.",
