    "id": "post-2024-08-26-7233890686087884801",
    "title": "Is it even possible to lead/manage a team without 1x live weekly me...",
    "date": "2024-08-26",
    "content": "Is it even possible to lead/manage a team without 1x live weekly meeting (to make sense of whatever happened unexpectedly last week and negotiate + commit to take unprecedented action over the coming week)?\"\n\"\nI've been trying to think through what might be feasible as you use tech to push remote/async/fractional work to its absolute limit, and the only conclusion I can come to is that pretty much every other meeting can be disintegrated (not including ad hoc breakouts for complex problem solving); but, the weekly recurring becomes actually significantly more important.\n\"\nSomehow, the worst place to be seems to be to be at the intersection of the drawbacks of both in-person AND remote, where there are lots of meetings (vs., say, a meaty piece of media like a long-form Loom video front-loaded with a Claude-generated bespoke headline + summary in a Slack thread), limited attendance/focus/action at the weekly, and nothing is recorded.\n\"\n\"Curious if anyone has successfully eschewed the weekly sync (maybe, just maybe, OSS projects and DAOs are able to do this with enough incentive alignment) ... I am deeply skeptical that this is feasible, but would love to learn from some other exotic management approach that is 100% remote AND async.",
