    "id": "post-2024-08-14-7229452691410763776",
    "title": "Google just crossed the privacy Rubicon",
    "date": "2024-08-14",
    "content": "Google just crossed the privacy Rubicon...\"\n\"\n...in a feature preview at their AI event this week.\n\"\nWe'll remember 2024 as the last year one could assume that a call was off-the-record.\n\"\nGoing forward, keep in mind, there is no \"user-AI privilege.\n\"\nThis kind of thing (Apple is rolling out something similar) will have knock-on effects that we're not prepared for.\n\"\nDoes this mean privacy is a luxury good now? \n\"\nThat confidentiality can only be guaranteed at an in-person meeting? \n\"\nDoes your home office need a SCIF?\n\"\nIf you've been following my posts on the implications of AI when it comes to privacy, transparency, and the accelerated rate at which private information now becomes common knowledge, then you know then that I've been banging this drum for a while. \n\"\nAs the cost of machine intelligence approaches zero and our ability to compress unstructured data becomes a utility, one should understand that the economic complement is proprietary, salient, high-fidelity, fresh data; as the scope of what be computed expands, so will the value of private record-keeping.\n\"\nThat means that even if you're a party to a conversation and are not recording it yourself, know that there's still a strong economic incentive for every other party to send that data, live, to somewhere where their digital exocortex can perform inference and give them an edge.\n\"\nIs this actually a big deal?\n\"\nOr am I blustering?\n\"\n\"Add a comment with your thoughts...",
