    "id": "post-2024-08-12-7228761284932972544",
    "title": "We need a digital EPA that imposes fines on mass polluters of the p...",
    "date": "2024-08-12",
    "content": "We need a digital EPA that imposes fines on mass polluters of the public web (i.e., \"AI slop\" shops).\"\n\"\n(In practice this means dinging low perplexity posts on social networks like LinkedIn so they get less visibility or something like that ‚Äî but it really drives me crazy how much garbage is being pumped out atm.)\n\"\nI have no problem using AI to help compress your ideas; in fact, it can help you elevate quality by asking questions in service proactively filling gaps before you post.\n\"\nBut if you're just acting as a shortcut-taking slop propagator with no regard for the hygiene of the digital public square (and at worst, using automation to horizontally scale your information pollution operation), you should be be on the receiving end of a Pigouvian tax that covers your negative externalities, straight up.\n\"\nThis can be solved IMO with platform policy and technology (eg Linkedin algorithm updates, boosting posts with cryptographically signed links to primary sources or person-specific biometric signatures) ‚Äî not law, literally ‚Äî but something needs to be done.\n\"\nAllowing high-quality information to get crowded out in the public conversation is bad for everyone; quality discourse retreats to private chat groups and otherwise fruitful connections that now, miraculously, happen at global scale get missed.\n\"\nJust say no to AI slop! \n\"\n\"A durable approach to AI adoption necessitates a deep commitment to quality over quantity always...",
