    "id": "post-2024-08-09-7227662249769811968",
    "title": "\"OKRs are a cargo cult",
    "date": "2024-08-09",
    "content": "OKRs are a cargo cult.\n\"\n- poster on another platform (and something that's, unfortunately, probably passed through the heads of anyone who's had to go through the unpleasant experience of a ham-fisted implementation)...\n\"\nThe truth is ‚Äî the OKR framework per se is well past the \"cargo cult\" phase, not unlike uppercase \"Agile\" or any other management framework from the 90s 'til today...\n\"\nThat said, in the spirit of the social technologies from which it's derived‚Äîwhich go past Wodtke and Doerr and Grove to Drucker and Sloan, and probably much further back still‚Äîgetting a lean, high-performing team to derive the right objective (and measure it three ways) based on proprietary data and a collective exercise in imagination and reason ‚Äî and then ruthlessly pursue it over the course of 3‚Äì4 months, with discipline around measurement, sharing insights, and running risky experiments every week will absolutely YIELD VALUE.\n\"\nNeeds the be the right context (crisis, enabling technology, or energetic/visionary leader), but it does work.\n\"\n(I've been doing this for years and refuse to work with clients of any size who can't commit to a single O and 3x KRs. We could go through the motions, and I could get paid a lot, but I have almost no confidence that that would be good for the client, so I just don't do it.)\n\"\nThe order-out-of-chaos approach is not for everyone, and attempts to implement it with folks who aren't operating on the frontier (the c-suite de facto should be, although that is unfortunately not always the case) is almost certain to be a misfit ‚Äî hence, the tendency toward degradation into cargo cult rituals when there's an attempt to roll this kind of thing out across more than one team.\n\"\n\"Have you ever tried OKRs at a company you've worked at? How'd it go?",
