    "id": "post-2024-08-07-7227097126944542721",
    "title": "I saw someone post on another platform about how they regularly run...",
    "date": "2024-08-07",
    "content": "I saw someone post on another platform about how they regularly run across \"tech people\" who don't regularly use AI, and it got me thinking...\"\n\"\n(He's right btw ‚Äî some of the most AI-skeptical people I've met are literal software engineers.)\n\"\nAlthough, as you might expect, younger folks and techies are a bit more likely to use tools like Claude and Chat, I've found the biggest & most reliable contributor to frequent use is a real \"HOLY SMOKES!\" magic moment, which in turn is usually contingent upon the person having some insane amount of pressure (e.g., a looming deadline, lack of resources) and so, because they're sort of backed into a corner, is willing to tinker with AI (in practice this means an obscene amount of furiously clicking, copying-and-pasting, etc.) to try to GSD, until it *clicks* and they realize the tech actually works.\n\"\nIt's basically over at that point‚Äîthere's no going back once you realize things that were literally impossible before are now possible.\n\"\nDiamonds are created under pressure; without that pressure (and perhaps a healthy dose of grit, hope, and humility), real AI adoption, the kind that leads to transformation, doesn't happen.\n\"\nThere are basically two ways to put this into practice as a manager/leader:\n\"\n1. SUBSTANTIALLY raise your expectations\n2. Run a time-bound hackathon\n\"\n\"The second one is fun and will get the creative juices flowing, but meaningful integration of the tech (and, truthfully, this is pretty uncomfortable, so be prepared) can only happen with 1.",
