    "id": "post-2024-07-15-7218745911487664128",
    "title": "AI is in this weird spot right now where it's clearly going to be m...",
    "date": "2024-07-15",
    "content": "AI is in this weird spot right now where it's clearly going to be most useful as a utility, but it's still barely in the product phase. \"\n\"\nWe're some number of 9s of reliability and orders of magnitude cost-wise from it all fading into the background (vs. the current one-off I/O mode).\n\"\nThings will get really interesting when basically everything that can be subject to inference will be (~2040?). \n\"\nUp until that point, I think many of the entrepreneurial opportunities will be realized via sustaining and expanding a nice competitive wedge (probably AI-enhanced services where software enhancements would have previously been prohibitively expensive to develop and deploy or some-such) and riding it all out through the full transition.\n\"\nThis'll take time, probably at least a generation; I'm excited to see people continue laying the groundwork for lean, AI-native companies that deliver goods and services but have architectures that take advantage of the tech, especially that are async, globally distributed, etc. (these really started last year IMO and will become more attractive in the years ahead relative to traditional tracks at non-AI native orgs that are currently struggling to, eg, go remote).\n\"\nIIRC, it took like 50 years for electricity to really make its way into the American economy. \n\"\n\"That feels about right to me as the time horizon over which some of the more visionary changes might work their way into mainstream life.",
