    "id": "post-2024-07-05-7215092119068143616",
    "title": "Has anyone seen creative use of organization-wide system prompts? \"...",
    "date": "2024-07-05",
    "content": "Has anyone seen creative use of organization-wide system prompts? \"\n\"\nOr system prompt engineering in enterprise settings? \n\"\nAt scale, you always run into the issue of there being gaps between strategy and execution. It would seem to me that at least as a complement to existing management approaches, the C-suite's strategic intent could be literally encoded into the system prompt of the enterprise generative AI tools that all employees are using so that it's always being taken into account in the context of what they're doing, in whatever small way.\n\"\n(One could imagine, too, additional context injected into the same system prompt depending upon the person's role within the organization, their department's objectives, etc. )\n\"\nI could also imagine that this isn't (yet) feasible‚Äîif, say, the prompt were too strict, and employees were overly constrained. \n\"\nBut it does seem to me like this could be a reasonable and valuable tool in the enterprise leadership toolkit that would work alongside, for example, a rigorous & unified OKR process and ultimately achieve both greater alignment while giving employees greater degrees of freedom (w/ say unlimited access to SOTA AI, integrated deeply into the org's proprietary data assets + operational workflows): the \"why\" is always there, but individuals get way more flexibility in re the what and the how.\n\"\n\"Anyone seen anything like this in the wild?",
