    "id": "post-2024-07-05-7215016156762378241",
    "title": "I think there's a lot of alpha be found in employing certain heuris...",
    "date": "2024-07-05",
    "content": "I think there's a lot of alpha be found in employing certain heuristics or frameworks, especially in corporate settings, that are either generally underrated or eschewing the ones that are overrated in favor of some orthogonal new approach. \"\n\"\nOften times, I think these sort of opportunities emerge because as certain arts become more mature, a precise technical jargon gets codified to support the transfer of what had been developed initially as a tacit body of knowledge. \n\"\nAnd ultimately, what can happen is that newcomers to the field end up mistaking in some sense the material or formal cause of the art for its final cause. \n\"\nOr in other situations, there may be some confusion about final cause, in which case the heuristic or approach may actually be underrated; people are likely to discount it because they don't realize that what's actually useful for is not necessarily what people assume it be used for.\n\"\nSo all this is very abstract, but I'll give you two examples.\n\"\nOne where think the heuristic is wildly underrated are personality assessments like DISC or StrengthsFinder. I often hear people denigrate these as being corporate horoscopes or roll their eyes and mention \"HR made me do this once\" or something to that.\n\"\nBut what I find interesting about this is that that low rating or importance that they assign to that particular heuristic is actually signaled by the term horoscope which implies some degree of prediction in an overly complex system where the formal causal model is unlikely to be rooted sufficiently in reality. \n\"\nNow I would argue that that's not the point of these diagnostics. It's actually to start a conversation where individuals (working especially on a cross-functional team) can come to terms with one another and generate testable hypotheses that they can then put into practice regarding how to communicate effectively, what type of work should be delegated to whom under what circumstances, the potential conditions under which certain members of the team would get energized, etc.\n\"\nPsych research demonstrates that even fundamental personality traits can change over the course of one or more decades. So clearly, these aren't set in stone to the extent that they can be relied upon for highly precise predictions, but they can be and SF I think in particular, made useful for reducing complexity when it comes to interpersonal team dynamics to the point that testable hypotheses can be generated and acted upon. \n\"\nThis ultimately leads, when used correctly, to higher performing cross-functional teams‚Äîbut only through subsequent process, not the diagnostic per se!\n\"\nOn the other hand, there are all kinds of complicated and esoteric terms of art in management, whether that's management of projects, products or corporations as a whole...\n\"\n\"(Cont'd in comments...)",
