    "title": "Every week, I practice what I preach and try to accelerate my consu...",
    "date": "2024-06-18",
    "content": "Every week, I practice what I preach and try to accelerate my consultancy's progress towards my highest-order goals with an AI-assisted OKR sync. \"\n\"\nHere are a few things I learned this week:\n\"\n‚Ä¢ Digital tools for not just remote but asynchronous communication and collaboration are getting better and better. I really believe if you're able to put constraints in place that force you to learn how to use them to solve problems for other people, it ends up being a major advantage because you're afforded many more degrees of freedom. \n\"\n‚Ä¢ For example, instead of automatically scheduling a call, I try to do as much discovery as I can upfront using AI tools to do deep research on a client or prospect, codify my analysis in a Figma  whiteboard, and then send a rich and comprehensive Loom  video with a call to action to take the next step. This could be scheduling a live call, talking to a voice agent who can ask the person specific questions, or even paying via a Stripe custom product link for a particular output or outcome that I propose. This has allowed me to align the hardest problems with the times of the day when my energy levels are highest.\n\"\n‚Ä¢ I'm continually surprised and fascinated by this liminal space between people and computers when it comes to delegation. As AI becomes more capable, hiring computers for a particular task rather than a person becomes a lot more sensible (eg MultiOn for information retrieval vs. or prior to hiring a freelance researcher.) However, there are cases where pure human labor is more reliable. This necessitates discernment when it comes to the what/when/how of \"who\" to delegate to, whether it's speed, quality, reliability, the amount of information that you're at liberty to share, etc.\n\"\nI'll continue to report back on what I learned but the bottom line is AI-powered humans that are distributed in space and time are a whole new category of workforce that I expect to emerge in interesting ways in the years ahead.\n\"\nFeel free to add questions in the comments.\n\"\n\"(I'll probably start publishing these updates on a more regular basis as I figure out what exactly it takes to ride the AI wave and build a business in a new way that the technology fundamentally enables.)",
