    "id": "post-2024-06-12-7206475478994485248",
    "title": "AI is starting to fundamentally change my relationship with time",
    "date": "2024-06-12",
    "content": "AI is starting to fundamentally change my relationship with time. \"\n\"\nSimilar to how computers, as they go from number crunching word crunching machines, are transforming the \"how\" and \"what\" of knowledge work via an expanding scope of delegatable tasks, these new capabilities also allow us to approach the \"when\" of work in a qualitatively different way by making it possible to \"pull\" future outcomes into the present. \n\"\nInstead of waiting for something to happen (e.g., that meeting next week), one might instead prioritize what to focus on in the context of ambitious, uncertain, longer-term goals. With AI assistance, it's possible to reduce uncertainty toward a final cause by crunching previously impossible volumes of information during high-energy, deep work sessions (which can also have the effect of bringing a bit more clarity to formal causes). \n\"\nOnce you've hit the limit of a time-boxed task, you can asynchronously tap into a liquid labor force, either through expert consults via voice agents or horizontally scalable task orders (eg for research and information retrieval) via platforms like Upwork by transforming the raw recordings you have on hand of salient contextual data and the recorded process (say, a Loom video) of you doing reps 1-10, providing enough specificity to guide successful task completion while also protecting sensitive info but running it all through a SOTA model like Claude first.\n\"\nThis dovetails nicely with cultivating a habit of communicating via rich media (vs. email or text only). This approach, previously time-consuming for the recipient of a long-form, unpolished video can now be summarized with a personalized set of headlines beforehand or interacted with directly via the other party's AI intermediary. \n\"\nConstant experimentation with AI over the past year (towards the end of helping a diverse array of clients across industries accelerate toward their BHAGs) has taught me to continuously question whether I might be able to delegate that next task that needs to get done (and I more or less know how to do), but don't find particularly energizing to sufficiently (and increasingly) competent machines.\n\"\nAs we continue to reorient the way we work with these new tools in hand, I anticipate we might be able to enter more fruitful relationship with time (and globally distributed collaborators) as well. \n\"\nInstead of being constrained by our calendars, waiting anxiously for our next back-to-back Zoom call, we can instead reduce pockets of uncertainty by tackling a queue of highly engaging, challenging, valuable chunks of work‚Äîand bring desired outcomes into our locus of control.\n\"\n\"(Screenshot from my OKR sync \"with\" Claude this morning ‚Äî I record a monologue that follows the same process I run with clients and engage in a little AI-powered thought partnership post to help me make sense of what I've learned over the past week.)",
