    "id": "post-2024-06-01-7202800042741510145",
    "title": "I have growing conviction that people are thinking about \"AI agents...",
    "date": "2024-06-01",
    "content": "I have growing conviction that people are thinking about \"AI agents\" in subtly wrong ways.\"\n\"\nThe power of these next-gen systems will not be primarily in their ability to take action on your behalf (e.g., send emails, order meals, post marketing content) but to augment your own imagination and reasoning faculties so you can make better decisions, especially \"one-way door\" decisions where the stakes are high, and you can justify substantial compute spend.\n\"\nIt's not so much that we'll be deploying agent swarms, but rather probes in latent and cyberspace, retrieving info (and very occasionally unsticking it from reality, though mostly through discourse with or observation of a human SME) and using that grounding/context (+, of course, your intentions and best guesses at other parties') in working memory to simulate an enormous variety of possible paths forward ‚Äî then, retrospectively, you can work backward from end states (all of which varying degrees of desirability) and tease out key \"facts\" that had an overweighted effect on the ultimate imagined outcome; through AI-powered scenario planning/counterfactual reasoning, you can then prioritize actions that reduce uncertainty in re what's actually the case and either boost the odds that you achieve the desirable outcome IRL or DQ dead ends faster.\n\"\nSort of like an augmented pre-mortem exercise or turbo-charged version of a \"what would have to be true...?\" line of questioning done in corporate strategy workshops.\n\"\n\"The gold nuggets will be those surprising possible branches that emerge through compute-intensive searches in simulated space, sort of like what happened w/ the new move \"discovered\" by AlphaGo.",
