    "id": "post-2024-05-08-7194115029951033344",
    "title": "Bring your own device? Now, CISOs need to be concerned about \"bring...",
    "date": "2024-05-08",
    "content": "Bring your own device? Now, CISOs need to be concerned about \"bring your own AI\". \"\n\"\nInstitutions, small and large, are staffed with a growing number of secret cyborgs who are figuring out, on their own, how to leverage state-of-the-art models ‚Äî everything from general-purpose tools to more specialized additions to their workflow. They're getting a lot more work done (and not telling anyone). \n\"\nThe knee-jerk reaction oftentimes is to ban these tools completely, even going as far as blocking certain domains from being accessed by company hardware. But that doesn't stop people from using ChatGPT or Claude on their own devices. \n\"\nThe only durable solution is to invest in an internal AI initiative. This isn't only a top-down mandate to keep information from leaking outside the organization; it also involves a concerted effort to identify opportunities for bottom-up innovation. \n\"\nAnd when the conditions are right, the c-suite should make some deep, focused bets in internal tooling. This can help turn those secret cyborgs into role models that might inspire more conservative colleagues to start adopting these tools, helping them take their professional craft to a totally new level.\n\"\nThe first step is making state-of-the-art model capabilities easy for tech-savvy employees to access. This can be done through simple web apps in controlled cloud environments, near future parity with consumer applications. There's also the bonus of gathering internal data and offering plug-and-play inferences from multiple model providers. \n\"\nOr, a turn-key organization-wide license can be enough, eg. ChatGPT Enterprise. \n\"\nFrom there, keep an eye on product analytics. You'll be able to see who the most forward-thinking users are. Then, start to create streamlined experiences that remove friction until you've got a product that appeals to early or late majority IT adopters.\n\"\n\"People will do what they're going to do, so your job in the C-suite is to help them make good decisions. Banning access simply does not work.",
