    "id": "post-2024-04-29-7190711488678903809",
    "title": "Simple business tip: \"\n\" \"\n\"Run small experiments",
    "date": "2024-04-29",
    "content": "Simple business tip: \"\n \nRun small experiments. \n \nAs a CEO, operating on the frontier is hard. \n \n‚Ä¢ You have to be innovative. \n‚Ä¢ You have limited resources to use. \n‚Ä¢ You have infinite possibilities to pursue. \n \nSo, how do we make decisions in such complex environments? \n \nAnswer ‚Üí \nWe build a culture of making small, tightly scoped bets that force you to act. \n \nAny time you get the hunch that there‚Äôs a better way of doing things, ask: \n \nHow do I develop a small experiment to validate my idea? \n \nThe goal is to get feedback. \n‚Ä¢ Fast \n‚Ä¢ Valuable \n‚Ä¢ Low cost \n \nIf the experiment works, double down & invest more. \n‚Ü≥ You‚Äôve found a useful direction to pursue! \n \nIf the experiment fails, pause & reflect. \n‚Ü≥ What just happened here? What did I learn?  \n \nArtfully designing small experiments illuminates the dark spots on the map. \n \nYou have a constant stream of data that increases visibility on the frontier. \n \nIt‚Äôs one of the strongest habits you can build for your business. \n \nPS ‚Äì It‚Äôs also the 1st habit I recommend CEOs build when integrating AI into their business. \n \n‚Ä¢ Run small AI experiments. \n‚Ä¢ Keep testing. \n \n\"What was the last ‚ÄúAI experiment‚Äù you designed & tested?",
