    "id": "post-2024-04-05-7182032654253383681",
    "title": "\"Intimacy\" is one of the most interesting variables in the Trust Eq...",
    "date": "2024-04-05",
    "content": "Intimacy\" is one of the most interesting variables in the Trust Equation, T = (credibility + reliability + intimacy)/self-orientation, and I think there are some interesting ways to use AI/digital media to cultivate it online, even asynchronously.\n\"\nIf you look at the very real phenomenon of these sort of digital-native parasocial relationships (w/ podcast hosts, influencers, reality show starts, et al) that have emerged over the past decade or so, it seems to point at there being something to \"more is more\" when it comes to publishing and building trust with an audience.\n\"\nVulnerability begets intimacy (taking little risks publicly), and I think as long as it's done prudently (i.e., you're neither propagating outright errors or revealing information that was entrusted to you by a third-party), it probably will start making sense to publish substantially more than you ever would have otherwise.\n\"\nWhy?\n\"\nWell, in addition to what I described above, AI allows the consumer of said information to delegate the initial information-gathering and synthesis process to their trusted AI intermediary. \n\"\nIf someone can run through all of your digital exhaust with a fine-tooth comb (and I guarantee this will soon become the norm) and find really precise points of contact for you two to connect on, then it does engender real trust and, perhaps more importantly, boosts the likelihood of a fruitful interaction.\n\"\nMy growing hunch is that the stable equilibrium of all this is one where professionals publish as much as they can (with the caveats above as a given) from their private digital memory repository, starting with what's in these AI notetaker systems, via new media like Delphi's AI clones.\n\"\nHow?\n\"\nReview everything you recorded over the past week, excise errors and information that was gifted to you by a third-party (e.g., everything said by others in the transcripts, stuff that you say that contains said information), tease out nuggets of insight and unresolved anomalies that emerged while you were serving said clients, work with AI as a thought partner to contend with them in an interview-style podcast (could be live and discursive or a monologue with really precise question prompts generated by, say, Claude 3 Opus for you based on the transcript data), and then upload it all (again, with redactions when/where appropriate) to your clone and then maybe one or two other channels, \"translated\" as appropriate (this is more-or-less how I create content for LinkedIn, derived from raw material captured in my professional \"reality show footage archive\").\n\"\n\"Going to continue experimenting with this and will report back...",
