    "id": "post-2024-03-14-7174024071746072578",
    "title": "Some folks have asked me to unpack my \"thinking naked\" concept a li...",
    "date": "2024-03-14",
    "content": "Some folks have asked me to unpack my \"thinking naked\" concept a little bit. So, I thought I would try to provide a bit of clarification. \"\n\"\nWhen I'm talking about \"thinking naked\" in the context of AI, I'm referring to a sort of paradox that I've encountered in using the technology more and more in interesting, different ways. Ultimately, the more, or I guess I should say \"more skillfully\", you use it, the less you actually use it. \n\"\nLiterally, you spend more time thinking about or doing things with basically zero input from AI systems. \n\"\nI've also referred to this, to the mechanism by which you get to this point, as AI acting as an \"on-ramp to a frontier.\" \n\"\nThat doesn't mean a literal physical place per se, but rather some pocket of invisible information or knowledge space that the system has never encountered based on its training data. Here, you as an embodied person grounded in reality need to conduct experiments, try things, and then make sense of whatever happens more or less on your own. \n\"\nTo put it simply, you're using AI as more of a filtering mechanism than a generative one whereby only the unresolved items that are most interesting and most important are quickly brought to your attention. Then, you need to really attend to them, which means really think hard about what the heck is actually going on and then what you should do about it. \n\"\nThat \"thinking hard\" part is more or less what I mean by \"thinking naked\". \n\"\nYou can certainly consult other folks in trying to make sense of whatever the anomalous data is, but you can't really get around the fact that you'll need to devote quite a bit of attention and work through it via your own natural faculties without machine assistance. \n\"\nIt's sort of like getting really hard-hitting, critical thinking questions in a high-quality English literature class, but applied to everything you encounter professionally. \n\"\n\"I hope that helps.",
