    "title": "I'm excited to share a video I usually only send to clients:\"\n\"\"\n\"h...",
    "date": "2024-03-09",
    "content": "I'm excited to share a video I usually only send to clients:\"\n\"\nhttps://lnkd.in/eWsR8hPS\n\"\nIn it, I distill a few of my key learnings from a year+ of putting generative AI technology like GPT-4 and Claude into clients' production workflows.\n\"\nWhy share it publicly? A few reasons:\n\"\n1. The tech is evolving fast, but I think many of the core principles will endure. I want to equip more people with know-how that can make easier to experiment at any point.\n\"\n2. I believe generative AI, used well, can make us more human, not less, and I think this is a really important idea for executives to consider before embarking on an AI integration initiative. By prudently delegating certain \"word-crunching\" tasks to machines, we free ourselves and our colleagues from administrative trivia, leaving room for greater degrees of creation, relation, contemplation, and orchestration.\n\"\n3. There's so much to figure out - how to identify opportunities, manage risks, and rethink roles. We need more voices and perspectives in the conversation and a diversity of compelling visions for a future with AI; that will only happen if more folks experiment and share what they learn.\n\"\nThe video covers a lot ‚Äî but, after recording it, I asked Claude to raise additional follow-up questions, and I thought I'd address a few of them:\n\"\n- How can a leader identify initial, high-leverage use cases? Start with a clear goal, an eager experimenter (maybe you!), and a task you know how to do but don't want to. Provide the AI inputs and instructions (especially via a diction tool like superwhisper) and iterate.\n\"\n- How do humans fit into the future of work? I believe we'll invest our surplus attention of energy into activities that make us more human‚Äîlike relationship-building and unbounded, curiosity-driven exploration of new problem spaces outside of the model's training data. We'll likely see a re-scrambling of roles (accompanied by latent needs that will have to be met to help people retool), but also huge opportunities for greater alignment between our strengths, interests, and the provision of higher-order goods, including via unprecedentedly liquid global labor markets.\n\"\n- What are some key risks to consider right now? Beware AI hallucinations, maintain human oversight always (don't delegate decision-making per se to a machine!), and put on your \"mind armor\" when going online (ads & dis-, mis-, and malinformation are becoming more potent). \n\"\nWe're in the early innings of a long game, and as I mentioned before, it's likely the fundamental technology will evolve quite a bit even in the next few months (and so, too, my own views on the space). BUT ‚Äî¬†it's never too late to get started!\n\"\n\"So, if you give it a watch, I'd love to hear your reactions, questions, and ideas in the comments (or through a DM).",
