    "id": "post-2024-02-26-7167881092136439808",
    "title": "Over the past 5 years, overconsumption of digital media has gotten ...",
    "date": "2024-02-26",
    "content": "Over the past 5 years, overconsumption of digital media has gotten a lot of attention. \"\n \nBut, in the last 12 months, I‚Äôve been experiencing an interesting reverse temptation. \n \nNot overconsumption. But hyper-production. \n \nWith AI, the balance can tip too far on the production side of the equation, too.  \n \nYou can: \n‚Üí Participate in so many conversations, \n‚Üí Produce so much content, \n‚Üí Get so many tasks done, \n‚Üí Work on engaging problems for so many clients across a wide range of industries, \n‚Üí Experiment with so many different ideas, \n \nThat there's almost a thrill‚Äîthe thrill of speed, of furiously knocking out items in the queue, producing, accelerating! \n \nNow, it becomes important to slow down every once in a while! \nTo step back and ask yourself: \n ‚ÄúAm I still moving on the right path? How is this meaningful?‚Äù \n \nSo, here's an antidote I call \"Thinking Naked\": \n \n‚Ü≥ For every hyper-productive, AI-enhanced hour, \n‚Ü≥ Set aside time for open-ended exploration without any particular goal; \n‚Ü≥ Become perceptive to the natural and social reality around you, appreciating and perceiving everything as it is; and \n‚Ü≥ Spend time with your thoughts, friends, family, and even strangers, sharing and exploring without a specific aim. \n \nAnd most importantly, completely away from technology! \n \nMy rule is: For every 1 hour I spend on the frontier, I'll spend another unplugged, away from the temptation to speedrun my task queue. \n \n\"Have you felt the thrill of AI hyper-productivity? How do you find time to unplug?",
