    "content": "Smaller businesses might just leverage AI to leap-frog bigger corporations. \"\n \nWe may be experiencing a ‚Äúhistory repeats itself‚Äù moment! \n \nBack in the 2000s, communications was the frontier. \n \nThe world was moving from the physical wire networks to wireless & satellite-based communications. \nThe technology was made available globally. \n \nAnd developing nations identified opportunities to skip the wired system entirely! \n \nAs a Result: \nSome developing nations with no ICT infrastructure were able to roll out wireless communications faster than developed nations. \n \nBut why didn‚Äôt the developed nations upgrade at least as quickly? \nAnswer ‚Üí The inertia of change management \n \nOnce anything grows in size, it loses its ability to quickly adapt, pivot & start new ways of working. There‚Äôs a deep commitment to a prior paradigm of work that‚Äôs difficult to completely overhaul. \n \nIt happens to startups. \nIt happens more to enterprises. \nAnd it can happen to entire states. \n \nToday, the same is true with AI. \n \nAI is globally available. \nAI presents a new way of working. \nAI meets you where you are in your journey of building a business. \n \nSmaller organizations can now find ways to delegate work to software that was previously not possible. And with nimble, quick-to-adapt teams, you might just have a strategic advantage to make the most of the AI opportunity. \n \nIf you start using AI today: \nBy the time enterprises and corporations involve AI in their day-to-day activities, you‚Äôll be miles ahead. \n \nJust like developing nations did, \n \nWe can embrace the new technology and directly start working with AI.  \nThe opportunity is as ripe as it has ever been :) \n \n*** \n \nWant more of my insights on leveling up with AI? \n‚Üí Follow me \n‚Üí Hit the üîî icon \n\"‚Üí Let‚Äôs become AI-enhanced digital workers",
