    "id": "post-2024-02-07-7161060165788585984",
    "title": "Building a company is like crossing a foggy river",
    "date": "2024-02-07",
    "content": "Building a company is like crossing a foggy river.\"\n\"\nThe \"foggy river\" metaphor is a mental model I like to share with executive teams at the beginning of a new OKR (objective & key results) engagement.\n\"\nRecently, I shared this‚Äîand a few related ideas‚Äîwith a new client before we dove into a 6-hour objective-setting exercise.\n\"\nBefore setting organization-wide goals, I think it's important to understand the purpose of those goals, and how we can think about goal-setting under conditions of incomplete information.\n\"\nHere's some of what we covered:\n\"\n- Managing uncertainty: the future is unknowable, so run experiments and disperse the fog\n- Companies as unified organisms, cells working together towards shared goals\n- Stepping stones vs. long-term plans: be agile and adapt along the way\n- Learning over progress: insights and information edge drive value creation\n- Quarterly cadence: breakthrough often comes at the 2nd/3rd month mark\n- Alignment = collective flow state. Misalignment = teams pulling apart\n\"\n\"Check out the attached video for more details.",
