    "id": "post-2024-02-06-7160633294177406976",
    "title": "Navigating a technology business is hard",
    "date": "2024-02-06",
    "content": "Navigating a technology business is hard. \"\n \nThe future isn‚Äôt just unknown. It‚Äôs unknowable! \n \nI use a mental model called ‚ÄúFoggy River‚Äù to simplify the goal-setting process: \n \nThe journey of starting and growing a company is similar to crossing a \"Foggy River.\"  \n \nThere are 3 elements: \n \n1/ Where you are ‚Üí (your current position on the map) \n2/ Where you want to be ‚Üí (your destination on the other side of the river) \n3/ Why you exist, AKA your mission ‚Üí (‚ÄúNorth‚Äù on your compass) \n \nBut here‚Äôs the problem: \nYou can see the eventual destination, but you can‚Äôt see what‚Äôs in the middle. \n \nThere‚Äôs fog everywhere. \n \nAnd there‚Äôs only 1 way to disperse the fog: \nBy taking action, uncovering more information that lets you see further down the river. \n \nSo the question of goal-setting is essentially this: \n \nFrom everything that you see (right now), which next stone will you step toward? \n \nThere‚Äôs always a trade-off: \n \n1/ You can prioritize depth  \n‚Ü≥ This means a faraway stone in a certain direction. Which means more progress! But what if our direction isn‚Äôt right? \n \n2/ You can prioritize breadth \n‚Ü≥ This means a closer stone that allows more degrees of freedom. Here we clear the fog before choosing a direction. But then we‚Äôre moving less fast :) \n \nNavigating this choice is the art of goal setting. \n \nBut in either scenario,  \n \nChoosing 1 stepping stone & aligning our entire team‚Äôs efforts towards this one objective does wonders for a business. \n \nI covered this in detail in a workshop with one of my clients. \n \nIf this analogy made sense, the workshop is a wonderful deep dive into how all the parts fit. \n \nComment \"Foggy River\" if you're interested in the whole workshop recording. \n \n*** \n \n\"And, let time me know your thoughts :)",
