    "id": "post-2024-01-15-7152660844638535680",
    "title": "In the Rwandan countryside, I learned more about networking than at...",
    "date": "2024-01-15",
    "content": "In the Rwandan countryside, I learned more about networking than at any seminar. \"\n \nI was part of the Legatum Fellowship at MIT, focused on delivering innovation to emerging markets.  \n \nThis journey took me to East Africa and Southeast Asia, to understand the challenges and identify opportunities to deliver better healthcare services in developing economies.  \n \n \n \nMy goal was to meet with local entrepreneurs, policymakers, and clinicians (endoscopists and gastroenterologists, specifically) to: \n \n- Gain firsthand insights \n- Build relationships, and \n- Ultimately use IT to help stakeholders share knowledge globally. \n \nArmed with just a backpack and a suit, I embarked on this exploratory trip. \n \n \n \nIn Rwanda, networking wasn't about exchanging business cards; it was about finding common ground and shared goals. \n \nSometimes over kebabs and bottles of Primus as I struggled to explain in broken French how Zoom and 4G hotspots could help endoscopists in Butare and Gisenyi deliver better care! \n \n \n \nI spent weeks backpacking, meeting diverse individuals from all walks of life. \n \nEach interaction, whether it was a meal with a banker or a conversation with a local entrepreneur, showed me how much undercapitalized talent resides in the world beyond our borders. \n \n \n \nThere are people in all countries with incredible potential and drive, particularly members of the younger generation who have grown up online. \n \nIt was a humbling and eye-opening experience that expanded my global perspective. \n \n \n \nReturning home, I carried with me a newfound appreciation for the diverse talents and perspectives that exist worldwide. \n \nI realized how there‚Äôs an opportunity for breakthrough innovation when diverse ideas, skills & experiences align towards a common goal.  \n \nA vast pool of untapped potential exists outside of the United States, in particular the self-taught and highly motivated \"digital native\" Gen Z'ers who are using the internet and AI to do new things and contribute to the global economy. \n \n \n \nIf you‚Äôre willing to venture beyond the U.S., in just a few clicks, you‚Äôll find high-energy, smart people who can make quick and substantial contributions to your business objectives. \n \nNow, I am truly bullish on trying to make your professional team as globally distributed as possible. It‚Äôs one of the biggest opportunities in our digitally connected world :) \n \n \n \nHave you worked with anyone outside of the US yet? \n \n\"Curious to hear how your experience was!",
