    "id": "post-2024-01-10-7150922096594886657",
    "title": "The success of the GPT Store will be, IMO, contingent upon OpenAI's...",
    "date": "2024-01-10",
    "content": "The success of the GPT Store will be, IMO, contingent upon OpenAI's ability to ultimately facilitate reliable GPT-to-GPT communication, almost entirely invisible to the user.\"\n\"\nOpenAI is in a bit of no-man's land ATM:\n\"\nOn one hand, specialized software with a traditional streamlined UI that limits what the user can do is often preferable to an open-ended chat interface. (This has become crystal clear to me as I've built artisanal web apps for SMBs that hook into OpenAI's APIs.)\n\"\nOn the other hand, the closer AI gets to the primary sources (with the extreme example being an always-on ambient computing device like Tab or the Humane Pin), the more value there is an a completely screenless, no-click experience.\n\"\nThe promise of the latter, a massive and I think desirable shift, necessitates solving some gnarly UX issues where the limiting factor is frontier model capability.\n\"\nMy guess is 4 isn't anywhere close to powerful enough to make this work. \n\"\nThe most basic version of retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), where GPT-4 queries web content via its browsing capabilities is still pretty unreliable, and reliability is a major concern with the ideal, more sophisticated RAG approach that allows GPTs safeguarding proprietary information and know-how to negotiate a mutually beneficial exchange (not unlike how we trust lawyers and business development professionals with sensitive information, assuming they'll use it optimally to further our interests).\n\"\nBut who knows? Maybe GPT-4.5/5/whatever search capabilities they're working on in the lab will sufficiently and reliably simulate imagination, reasoning, and negotiation. (Tall order, but possible!)\n\"\nAnd of course there's the issue of security ‚Äî there is NO WAY I'm putting proprietary, let alone sensitive info into a custom GPT today.\n\"\nYou wouldn't hire a lawyer who carries around copies of all your secrets and can be easily coaxed into handing them over...that is, unfortunately, a risk of the technology as it exists today.\n\"\n\"That said, I'm excited for this first step toward a machine-to-machine economy that allows us to stay focused on what's important, delegate more rote tasks to machines, and be fairly financially rewarded for our expertise‚Äîa nice alternative to the ad model‚Äìsupported platforms that have prioritized capture of attention over creation of new knowledge.",
    "excerpt": "The success of the GPT Store will be, IMO, contingent upon OpenAI's ability to ultimately facilitate reliable GPT-to-GPT communication, almost entirely...",
