    "title": "What's something you wish you had time to do but never really get t...",
    "date": "2023-12-15",
    "content": "What's something you wish you had time to do but never really get to?\"\n\"\nThat to-do that would not only be fun and energizing but, if things go right, really move the needle for your business?\n\"\nI'm talking about \"micro R&D\" tasks that business owners barely get time to tackle: e.g., serendipitous coffee chats with other leaders, opportunities to work at a new skill like email copywriting, an unbroken chunk of deep work \"getting to know\" cutting-edge AI assistants like ChatGPT and Claude, figuring out how to hire top global talent through Fiverr or even Twitter.\n\"\nIt's through those little experiments on the frontier that business owners (and leaders generally) might find those unexpected breakthrough insights and opportunities to take things to the next level.\n\"\nBut, we're often so busy attending to just keeping the train the tracks (and all the support tasks below the surface of what customers and even employees ever see) that it can feel impossible to carve out that focused exploratory time.\n\"\nWhat I love about AI, and was discussed on a recent No Priors episode with former CEO of Square, Alyssa Henry, is that as SMBs get access to serious IT capabilities, \"latent demand\" is unlocked: unburdened by those weighty support tasks (and the traditionally high costs of bespoke IT integrations), businesses can not only become more efficient, but also do NEW things.\n\"\nIt's in those 0 to 1 moments that innovation happens, even at a small scale. Those little opportunities to innovate (and strengthen customer relationships) compound, leading to overall improvements in product & service quality, customer experience, and even employee engagement.\n\"\n\"(Link to episode in the comments.)",
