    "id": "post-2023-11-17-7131338393728212992",
    "title": "One of the more interesting lines in the Biden Executive Order on A...",
    "date": "2023-11-17",
    "content": "One of the more interesting lines in the Biden Executive Order on AI is the line about ‚Äúundue worker surveillance.‚Äù\"\n\"\nAs more companies start to realize that the digital exhaust generated by employees‚Äîwhich is currently mostly captured in emails, Slack messages, and documents in enterprise storage‚Äîis actually the raw material that you need to get the most out of AI, there will be a growing incentive to set up a high-fidelity panopticon that monitors absolutely everything workers do in the course of their jobs.\n\"\nThis, I anticipate, will be a growing issue in the years ahead; we'll have to reconsider how we think about standard employer-employee agreements and who actually owns not just work products, but the tacit knowledge that is gained and deployed over the course of a worker‚Äôs career.\n\"\nShould worker surveillance be banned? (Can it?)\n\"\n\"Or is it possible that as we're able to more easily capture tacit knowledge and turn it into a capital asset thanks to AI: that it may make more sense for employers to offer employees more compensation, especially in equity, in exchange for a copy of their know-how as it evolves during their tenure at the company?",
