    "id": "post-2023-11-14-7130206813530025984",
    "title": "I sometimes wonder if we'll look at the first 20 years of the 21st-...",
    "date": "2023-11-14",
    "content": "I sometimes wonder if we'll look at the first 20 years of the 21st-century similar to how we view the early Industrial Revolution.\"\n\"\nThere was tremendous progress, innovation, and broader access to goods and information, BUT...\n\"\nThere were plenty of what economists call \"negative externalities\": byproducts like pollution (think: a very sooty London) or, in the case of the early consumer, ad-driven internet, \"information pollution\" and, with the rise of social media platforms, hyper-fragmented attention.\n\"\nSeen purely as a functional tool, an internet-connected computer should, as Steve Jobs so clearly illustrated with his \"bicycle for the mind\" metaphor, accelerate the user's progress toward his or her goal.\n\"\nNow, whenever we pour our attention into our screens, we're tempted to stray from our original path by the charismatic tips-of-icebergs that invite us into the depths of a funnel, where we incrementally part ways with our time, personal information, and ultimately money.\n\"\nWhile the linked article headline is a bit polemical, I do think it's worth meditating on what we've collectively learned‚Äîas consumers, marketers, internet entrepreneurs, and technology users more broadly‚Äîand what alternative architectures for accessing and benefiting from digital media might be afforded to us by technology like AI and privacy-preserving consumer hardware.\n\"\nIs it possible that we might soon be able to move to a new paradigm, where there are fewer negative information externalities and information is filtered and indexed first through an intelligent mediator (e.g., on-device LLM)‚Äîand perhaps even synthesized into a coherent report‚Äîbefore it enters your mind?\n\"\nI'm optimistic, especially as AI-native \"ambient computing\" hardware like the Humane‚Ñ¢ Pin come to market, that we'll have the opportunity to at least make more informed choices about how we traverse the web.\n\"\nAnd, ultimately, as the internet's center of gravity shifts from ad-driven consumer platforms like Google and Instagram to frontier foundation models, the most prized commodity also shifts from human attention to valuable know-how.\n\"\nWhile the platforms of the past 20 years grew more powerful the more attention was flowing through them (hence, e.g., acquisitions of companies for their highly engaged userbases), the foundation models become more valuable the more instrumentally valuable their training is (hence the recent push by the AI Labs for more high-quality data that's not on the public internet).\n\"\nThis subtle difference may have a huge effect on how companies reach and serve customers, how the next generation of entrepreneurs thinks about where commercial opportunities lie, and‚Äîperhaps most importantly‚Äîthe nature of our relationships with and through digital media and information technology.\n\"\nI, for one, am ready for the chance to enjoy a \"cleaner internet.\n\"\n\"https://lnkd.in/ePcgaPMT",
