    "id": "post-2023-11-05-7126933435108990977",
    "title": "It just hit me that what the iPhone did to hardware, AI will do to ...",
    "date": "2023-11-05",
    "content": "It just hit me that what the iPhone did to hardware, AI will do to software.\"\n\"\nWe used to have a million different physical products and devices to meet our needs for communication, getting news, listening to music, taking photos, etc.\n\"\nThen, BOOM, it all collapses into the consumer hardware singularity of the iPhone.\n\"\nAnd software becomes the complement that it makes sense for entrepreneurs to build their businesses around.\n\"\nEvery time OpenAI releases new capabilities, there's a meme about \"1,000 startups just died,\" and I think that's just going to accelerate in the years ahead.\n\"\nSo if foundation models (and AI lab products) absorb most software like the iPhone did to consumer cameras, trad media, etc, then what should entrepreneurs build their businesses around?\n\"\nMy hunch is that it's DATA: specifically high-quality, high-fidelity data that exists far outside of the pre-training datasets.\n\"\nData from the real world. Data that is novel and interesting and compressible. Data acquired through the process of solving real problems for real people that have never been solved before (NOT decadent ZIRP wealth transfer schemes).\n\"\nIf you digitize the result and the process across a wide range of scenarios (given one or two dimensions held constant), you'll have nearly everything you need to create a capital asset that fits into the AI value chain; I anticipate that there will be interesting and novel business models that enable the commercialization of that data as it inevitably moves along the gradient of private to public good.\n\"\nIn practice, this gives us three questions to consider:\n\"\n1. Am I, an entrepreneur building software, building something that will be commoditized by and absorbed into the foundation model borg?\n\"\n2. In what \"direction\" can I point my attention such that I move toward an as-yet-uncolonized pocket of latent space where I can both make novel discoveries and serve my neighbor?\n\"\n\"3. How can I construct a self-improving machine that generates and makes sense of the experimental data acquired on that frontier? (And do I even really need to build software at all?)",
