    "id": "post-2023-10-03-7115021227747889152",
    "title": "\"As AIs learn more about you, their usefulness will go up, though t...",
    "date": "2023-10-03",
    "content": "As AIs learn more about you, their usefulness will go up, though the full implications of AIs that make complex inferences about you is currently unclear.\n\"\nI think this one the most important points in Prof. Ethan Mollick's latest piece.\n\"\nSince the future is not just unknown but unknowable, every time we interact with other people or make decisions based on predictions, we always have the choice to give someone the benefit of the doubt or remain open to the idea that past behavior or data, even if totally verified, that is not necessarily a predictor of future outcomes.\n\"\nI think there will be a growing temptation to make sharp judgments and extrapolate based upon the excruciatingly high-fidelity primary sources that our various AI assistants will have access to.\n\"\nFor example, hoovering up all of somebody's digital exhaust and compiling a dossier with recommendations to prepare you for a fruitful first time meeting with someone.\n\"\nAlthough much of that information will likely be useful, especially as a sort of on-ramp to topics and areas of information space where you and the other party are most likely to have common interests and help each other out, it is the responsibility of both parties to be open to new data that's not in the dossier and the possibility that genuinely new things could happen during the interaction that defy even the most confident inferences and predictions that these seemingly omniscient models make prior to the interaction.\n\"\n\"This problem of prediction versus non-judgmental openness is going to be a major grounds for cultural debate and in the years ahead as we try to figure out the right way to navigate this new AI-human symbiosis.",
