    "id": "post-2023-09-28-7113211457193828354",
    "title": "Although I am a technophile (more recently, an occasional ‚ÄúAI maxim...",
    "date": "2023-09-28",
    "content": "Although I am a technophile (more recently, an occasional ‚ÄúAI maximalist‚Äù), I contend that for each hour spent assisted by personal computation‚Äîfor each cognitive cycle augmented by intelligent machines‚Äîan equal quantity should be invested sans AI. ‚ÄúThinking naked,‚Äù if you will.\"\n\"\nWhen I‚Äôm at my best and I need to unplug, I REALLY unplug. (It‚Äôs that liminal online/offline space in between the ends of a barbell-shaped relationship with digital media that cognition gets mixed up.) I would counsel other AI enthusiasts to consider taking a disciplined approach to going tech-less: front-loading workdays with unmediated contemplation.\n\"\nWhy?\n\"\nWell, there are, broadly, two modes of knowledge work: that which generates experimental data and that which makes sense of it (which then precedes another round of contact with reality, segued via hypothesis generation‚Äîand so on). This is all towards the end of knowledge production‚Äîand, when we're especially fortunate, meaning-making. Those heuristics one discovers to work with a degree of reliability in his or her quest to move a particular project forward are the source of differentiated leverage (and, for commercial purposes, profit); if this technƒì can also be made generally useful as a capital and/or public good, it helps us all move THE project forward by catalyzing other seekers as they respectively drive toward‚Äîin machine learning terms‚Äî‚Äúcompression progress.‚Äù\n\"\nMy personal experience would lead me to believe that dedicating time before noon to thinking, simply, sometimes for hours before uttering a single word (though occasionally supported by committing a subset of these thoughts to ‚Äúshort-term memory‚Äù in slow longhand, e.g., attached) is an essential complement to those AI-as-rocket-fuel hyper-divergent/convergent excursions through latent space.\n\"\nGoing without said time for too long inevitably leads to cognitive fragmentation and some variation of \"TikTok brain\"; no one wants this.\n\"\nAbout two weeks ago, I broke a cardinal rule: ‚ÄúDo not check your email (let alone Twitter!) until 1pm. This became a habit, and I allowed my precious morning attention to be swallowed by a queue of digital trivia.\n\"\nIt wasn‚Äôt until today, just after sunrise in the quiet car of the Amtrak to Penn Station, that I was able to bring order to the various data spread across clients, industries, and disparate domains that had accumulated at the periphery of my mind‚Äôs eye.\n\"\nThose first fifteen minutes of raw boredom‚Äîthat paradoxical sensation of over- and under-stimulation‚Äîwere, as they always are, uncomfortable; but, insights  emerged (as they always do), and in stark contrast to the brief thrill (and flood of cortisol) that comes with diving into my email queue, I am sated; I have no regrets.\n\"\n\"In the long-term, I hope that AI becomes nigh-invisible, and we can usher in a long-prophesied ‚Äúcalm computing‚Äù paradigm; until then, here‚Äôs a friendly PSA: remember to periodically remove the exocortex, be bored, and think for yourself.",
