    "id": "post-2023-09-20-7110396789140148224",
    "title": "Serious question",
    "date": "2023-09-20",
    "content": "Serious question...\"\n\"\nWho would you trust more?\n\"\n5 layers of highly competent human managers or an AI assistant with complete access to your enterprise repository?\n\"\nSounds like sci-fi, but it soon won't be.\n\"\nLet's assume (conservatively) that AI hallucinates 20% of the time (in other words, it introduces noise into a single message such that 20% of that message is not signal).\n\"\nLet's also assume (charitably) that humans \"hallucinate\" only 5% of the time.\n\"\n0.80 > 0.95^5\n\"\nThat means that, as a CEO, it would be a rational decision to query the raw facts (e.g., internal messages, meeting recordings and transcripts) directly via a (dispassionate) AI intermediary vs. 5 layers of management (all people with their own goals, which may or may not be aligned with the organization's highest-order concern).\n\"\nWe can be relatively certain that AI hallucination rates will decrease AND more primary source data is going to be digitized (e.g., via recorded meetings and AI notetakers like Otter.ai) and made legible to LLM-powered agents.\n\"\nI've already been pretty compelled by the little tastes I've gotten of what's coming over the past month:\n\"\n- using long context window AI‚Äîlike Anthropic's Claude‚Äîto retrieve facts from 3 months ago at a quarterly reflection, straight from the meeting transcript (even with some counterfactual reasoning on top)\n\"\n- asking AI, as my trusted advisor, to point out key bits of info I may have missed during a multi-hour negotiation (literally as soon as the meeting ended!), helping me illuminate my own blind spots\n\"\n- asking AI to act a trusted advisor to one of my prospects, reviewing long-form transcripts from previous client workshops and live working sessions I've delivered, and assessing whether or not I'd be a fit, given the needs they shared during a discovery call for me to share with them (it produced a long-form memo that protected PII, while also supporting claims with direct quotes)\n\"\nAI is, IMO, going to have a huge impact on the way corporations are run, including (and especially) management per se.\n\"\nWhat are some managerial responsibilities to which AI is unlikely to serve as a substitute?\n\"\n\"What, within the art of management, is most complementary to this all-seeing, highly capable, information hyper-retrieval AI?",
