    "id": "post-2023-09-15-7108524843217641472",
    "title": "‚ÄúWith AI, the only constant is change; the focus should be on solvi...",
    "date": "2023-09-15",
    "content": "‚ÄúWith AI, the only constant is change; the focus should be on solving problems.‚Äù\"\n\"\nI recently had a compelling conversation with Karl Yeh, another indie consultant helping business owners take advantage of the latest generation of AI.\n\"\nHere are some of the core insights that came up during our discussion:\n\"\n1Ô∏è‚É£ Change is Inherent to the Technology\n\"\nWhat It Means: AI is evolving at an unprecedented rate. As new foundation models come online, their capabilities are distributed almost instantaneously, meaning the cycle time between breakthrough and implementation CAN be unprecedentedly short.\n\"\nWhy It Matters: Committing to a particular technology is likely not a sound strategic decision, as something better is likely to come online soon (and probably sooner than you think).\n\"\n2Ô∏è‚É£ AI is a Means to a Real-World End\n\"\nWhat It Means: For implementations to succeed, consultants should focus on what the client is seeking to achieve with AI, and then run quick, iterative experiments to assess technical feasibility without getting lost in the technical weeds.\n\"\nWhy It Matters: The better the technology works, the more invisible it becomes. Staying focused on the end goal mitigates the risk of getting sidetracked by shiny AI toys (and premature optimization rabbit holes) and ensures better results for all parties‚Äîin both the short- and the long-run.\n\"\n3Ô∏è‚É£ No Experts, Only Pioneers\n\"\nWhat It Means: Expertise in AI is more about a process of continuous learning and experimentation than having a set of fixed knowledge.\n\"\nWhy It Matters: Setting realistic expectations is crucial (there will be bugs!), but there‚Äôs also the exciting possibility of uncovering unexpected, groundbreaking capabilities during the engagement.\n\"\n4Ô∏è‚É£ Cut Through the Hype\n\"\nWhat It Means: While chatbots are often touted as the future, customer-facing chatbot technology, even with the latest LLMs, still leaves a lot to be desired; this is true of other \"sexy\" AI use cases that get a lot of attention in the media.\n\"\nWhy It Matters: Focusing on unsexy but effective internal workflow automation and business operations is a pragmatic approach that can deliver robust, immediate value.\n\"\n5Ô∏è‚É£ Workflow Integration\n\"\nWhat It Means: Changing someone‚Äôs workflow is a big ask. Meeting users where they are before asking them to make a significant change (or even a seeming insignificant one, like opening a new window) is essential.\n\"\nWhy It Matters: Making AI accessible within existing workflows (like Slack or Teams) can significantly ease the transition and increase adoption. Great tip, Karl Yeh !\n\"\n\"I really enjoyed my conversation with Karl and look forward to sharing more insights that emerge from our future conversations, as well as those with other practitioners in the space, as we all experiment and learn together in real time on the #AI frontier.",
