    "date": "2023-08-05",
    "content": "üò§ One thing that really bothers me about what's being discussed in A.I. right now is the narrow focus on efficiency.\"\n\"\nüìâ It's often framed in terms of job loss, cost cutting, and replacement.\n\"\nü§ñ There's even a story floating around right now about an entrepreneur boasting about replacing his customer support staff with chatbots. Not the right approach IMO.\n\"\nüí™ Now, if instead you're thinking about how to use artificial intelligence to not just gain efficient, but also be more EFFECTIVE (and do new things), that's a healthier approach.\n\"\nüí∏ Even if you lean out your team out by increasing individual throughput, you'll then have access to the same internal resources and capabilities; you've freed up capital that you can invest elsewhere.\n\"\n‚è≥ When things go right with AI implementations, you're going to see immediate results. Best case, you and your staff get up to 50% (even 80%) of your time back.\n\"\nThat's a lot!\n\"\nüß† You'll have all this surplus human attention & brainpower (the most valuable resources on the planet) that, with the right mindset, each team member can start putting into \"micro R&D.\n\"\nüëç Google got this right with their \"20% free time.\n\"\nüó∫Ô∏è Collectively, and not always just in the long run, the entire company benefits from this objective-free exploration: the freedom to explore during some of the time saved allows motivated team members to experiment, create, and discover entirely new ways of doing things that could unlock your business's next market or product breakthrough.\n\"\nü§î So, what would you do with all that excess capital freed up by bespoke AI integrations?\n\"\nüí∞ If you could quadruple your R&D budget, what would you invest it in?\n\"\n\"#artificialintelligence #research #innovation",
