    "title": "Are AI-powered developer tools like GitHub Copilot an on-ramp to an...",
    "date": "2023-07-04",
    "content": "Are AI-powered developer tools like GitHub Copilot an on-ramp to an additional $10,000,000,000,000 (yes, trillion) in global GDP?\"\n\"\nAs I use these tools more and more on a daily basis, my growing suspicion is that the answer is, \"yes.\n\"\nMicrosoft recently published the results of a study that shows that software engineers are already getting, on average, a 30% boost in productivity from Copilot: https://lnkd.in/ec9w7yMM\n\"\nAnd not only are developers writing more code faster, they're also reporting more fulfillment and greater levels of job satisfaction, all of which is without access to an even more powerful version of Copilot (\"Copilot X\"), which is available now in limited preview.\n\"\nThis next release, which bundles multiple tools into a comprehensive suite, is showing a lot of promise by more deeply integrating OpenAI's state-of-the-art foundation model, GPT-4, into every step in a developer's workflow.\n\"\nI wouldn't be surprised that if in late 2024, at the intersection of a number of these mutually reinforcing technologies‚Äîespecially foundation models with larger context windows, image inputs (and multimodality more broadly), more sophisticated retrieval augmented generation, extremely accurate speech-to-text input via Whisper, and even spatial computing with Apple's Vision Pro headset‚Äîthat you'll see more people who aren't traditional programmers or software engineers starting to write code and doing so at blazing speeds.\n\"\nWho knows‚Äîmaybe we'll even add another order of magnitude to this projected productivity boost?\n\"\nBased on my experiences with the technical preview, lots of hands-on experience with VR at my last startup, and a bit of optimism, I think this could be a much bigger deal than Microsoft is letting on...\n\"\n\"#ai #developer #software",
