    "id": "post-2023-06-26-7079229791815520257",
    "title": "With great (indexing) power, comes great responsibility",
    "date": "2023-06-26",
    "content": "With great (indexing) power, comes great responsibility...\"\n\"\nFor most of human history, information was, out of necessity, synthesized, codified, and sorted (\"indexed\") by third-party authorities.\n\"\nNow, thanks to AI, that's changing in unprecedented ways.\n\"\nOne of my favorite use cases for large language models like OpenAI's GPT-4 is \"personalized indexing,\" which is just a fancy way of saying that you can delegate \"pre-reads\" (or \"pre-watches\" or \"pre-listens\") of long-form content‚Äîand ideally primary sources‚Äîto AI models that are aware of your personal goals, preferences, and level of expertise on a given topic.\n\"\nInstead of relying solely on the interpretation of humans (individuals and institutions) of raw material, you can choose to get a second opinion from an AI pipeline, which will process and summarize huge amounts of info, giving you the rough shape of things in exactly the format that you can handle + surfacing anomalies that you can invest your attention into exploring (and, perhaps, capitalizing upon for the purposes of product development and entry into new markets).\n\"\nI've personally put this into practice‚Äîand gotten substantial value!‚Äîby mining podcast backlogs to mine insights that catalyze clients' market discovery initiatives.\n\"\nOn one hand, this is great: you can process information at a much higher clip and surface practical insights without needing to hire a huge team (or wait for them to create the reports).\n\"\nThis was always the promise of digital media; however, because the advertising-driven business model came to dominate the consumer internet over the past two decades, the \"index\" (i.e., the feed-populating social media algorithms and search engines) was never really aligned with your personal interests. It always took advertisers' and the platforms' objectives into account, often as the primary drivers of index design.\n\"\nNow, it looks like we'll be paying for what we consume when it comes to AI, which means we'll be adding \"AI\" to our monthly utility expenditures along with gas and electricity. This is ultimately good: We won't have to worry (at least not as much) that our \"machine-generated indices\" are working more in the interest of a third-party's rather than our own.\n\"\nOn the other hand, this means that unifying narratives (interpretations of events) will likely fragment further, and reasoning errors are likely to compound as some people choose to prefer indices that reinforce their beliefs, rather than test hypotheses in the interest of achieving real-world results.\n\"\nThat said, I remain extremely optimistic about the upside of this unprecedented power to process, prioritize, and present information straight from the source, especially for the next generation that learns how to harness these technologies to make sense of pockets of information on the frontier of human knowledge!\n\"\n\"As context windows expand, inference speeds increase, and per-token prices drop, we'll see huge impact from AI-enabled personalized indexing.",
