    "id": "post-2023-06-19-7076678100859678720",
    "title": "üìö Will being able to read and write even be necessary in the Age o...",
    "date": "2023-06-19",
    "content": "üìö Will being able to read and write even be necessary in the Age of AI? ü§ñ\"\n\"\nAI begs a lot of questions that we haven't had to grapple with for a long time, and I think that novelty and that weirdness will, understandably, freak people out.\n\"\nEven basic literacies developed post-industrialization: reading, writing, and arithmetic‚Äîare those still the correct educational fundamentals?\n\"\nDo people really have to read and write if they can just speak to computers in natural language?\n\"\nAs I've discussed with Sam Blackman, maybe at least as important for the next generation of students to be able navigate complex systems, attain greater degrees of self-knowledge, contribute to short-term projects on interdisciplinary \"liquid teams.\n\"\nIronically, \"writers\" (for much of human history) didn't write anything down at all.\n\"\nThey were extremely talented thinkers. They were observant; they were grounded, and they were masters of discursive, verbal communication.\n\"\nAristotle, Socrates, et al: Their STUDENTS wrote down what they said, even if they were the \"authors.\n\"\nWith low-cost generative AI, we're all afforded the freedom to communicate through the medium that is the best fit (for us AND our interlocutors).\n\"\nWe'll no longer need to toil with pens, sheafs of paper, or clunky keyboards to codify our thoughts‚Äîand, especially if you're a parent with young kids, that's worth spending some time thinking about as AI makes its way into our daily personal and professional lives!\n\"\n\"#ai #writing #education #artificialintelligence",
