    "id": "post-2023-06-15-7075244837377060864",
    "title": "Is innovation more of an art or a science?\"\n\"\"\n\"According to Tom Bo...",
    "date": "2023-06-15",
    "content": "Is innovation more of an art or a science?\"\n\"\nAccording to Tom Borger‚Äîan innovation expert with plenty of experience as an entrepreneur trapped in a corporate body‚Äîthe answer may surprise you.\n\"\nIt's 100% a science!\" üî¨\n\"\nThere's an essential role for creativity in the scientific method, and it's in the first three steps:\n1. üëÄ Observation, \n2. ü§® Questioning, and\n3. ü§î Hypothesis generation.\n\"\nWhile we often speak about innovation in terms of inspiration and breakthroughs, the iterative process of hypothesis testing, data collection, and analysis are as important.\n\"\nIdeation alone isn't sufficient.\n\"\nIt's ideation + experimentation that yields innovation!\n\"\nInnovation teams transform data from experiments into insights that either drive immediate action, or provide additional observational fuel for the next cycle of inquiry, hypothesis generation, and investigation.\n\"\nTom knows. He's spent decades helping startups and large corporations use this form of the \"scientific method\" to drive innovation, enter new markets, and unlock new sources of revenue.\n\"\nNow, in a world where cutting-edge technologies (like artificial intelligence) are opening up opportunities to drive innovation at an accelerating rate, it's never been a better time to launch IT-driven innovation initiatives and catalyze learning by observing, questioning, hypothesizing, testing, analyzing, and observing (lather, rinse, repeat)... üîÑ\n\"\n#innovation #scientificmethod #creativity #digitaltransformation\n\"",
