    "id": "post-2023-05-25-7067540362164109312",
    "title": "If AI ultimately makes us all 2‚Äì5x more productive, the obvious que...",
    "date": "2023-05-25",
    "content": "If AI ultimately makes us all 2‚Äì5x more productive, the obvious question is, \"What are we going to do with all that extra time?\"\n\"\nMy rough guess is that we'll invest more attention into activities that complement AI (and ultimately make us more human):\n\"\nüé® Creation: Doing new things. Venturing forth on the frontier, solving problems you've never solved before (and, ideally, no one else has). AI will still be useful, a tool for accelerating the convergent/divergent creative process.\n\"\nü§ù Relation: Building trust-based relationships by paying close attention to what's said (and not said) and maintaining a charitable posture. This close attention can be enhanced by substantial prep: sufficient research via AI-assisted analysis of the other person's digital exhaust/online footprint.\n\"\nüôè Contemplation: Tech-free cogitation. Uninterrupted reasoning, imagination, and meditation on the raw inputs you're collecting on the frontier during your creative activities.\n\"\n‚öôÔ∏è Orchestration: Managing bespoke, AI-powered loops. You'll need to keep an eye on your \"dashboard\" and decide when to delegate tasks, wind up new processes, and shut down ones that no longer serve your longer-term goals.\n\"\nBUT, it's worth noting that each of these types of activity can descend into negative/unbalanced versions:\n\"\nWithout a production function, you can end up mindlessly consuming novel information; and even when you're producing, you still risk imprudently delegate parts of the creative process (e.g., pruning bad ideas) to AI.\n\"\nInstead of building relationships with real humans, there will be, unfortunately, a growing temptation to invest attention into \"relationships\" with charismatic AI-powered sycophants. And although more background info via a \"digital exhaust dossier\" can help you save time and build trust, it can just as easily be used to manipulate, exploit, and deceive; be very careful with this info.\n\"\nContemplating is NOT \"watching Netflix to relax.\" It's pure, uninterrupted thinking; however, given a poor information diet, unchecked assumptions may lead one to arrive at absurd conclusions or even become deluded. Real-world experiments are critical for mitigating this particular issue.\n\"\nFinally, unskilled orchestration can lead to hyper-fragmented attention (think about cmd+tabbing b/w email and Twitter and Slack and Docs and...) or over-optimization, whereby processes that no longer \"work\" given an evolving landscape and higher-order objectives aren't properly obsolesced, and your rate of innovation slows or even stops.\n\"\nSoftware engineers are already able to produce quality work, faster, thanks in part to AI tools like GitHub Copilot and ChatGPT Plus (w/ GPT-4).\n\"\nSoon, the rest of us will have hyper-tailored AI copilot assistants that make information retrieval, problem-solving, and publication of new knowledge substantially more efficient.\n\"\nSo, what are you going to do with all that extra time?\n\"\n\"Something worth thinking about sooner rather than later!",
