    "id": "post-2023-05-24-7067172842445930496",
    "title": "How do you run weekly executive meetings that don't suck?\"\n\"\"\n\"Here...",
    "date": "2023-05-24",
    "content": "How do you run weekly executive meetings that don't suck?\"\n\"\nHere are 10 key takeaways from my presentation to Vidya Santhanam's Fitbots OKRs community:\n\"\nüöÄ Inject Your Meetings with the Excitement of a Netflix Binge: Status update meetings can transform into engaging sessions that team members look forward to attending, much like anticipating the next episode of a favorite Netflix series.\n\"\nüß† Activate the Organizational \"Nervous System\": By focusing only on the most pleasant or painful organizational \"nerve endings\" you can surface the most pertinent pieces of information and streamline decision-making during OKR check-in meetings.\n\"\nüéØ Empower Teams to Gamble on Greatness: Attendees should be held accountable for surfacing quality information relating to their objectives and key results, not necessarily for achieving them. This empowers team members to take risks and to remain aligned on their goals.\n\"\nüî• Energy and Enthusiasm Aren‚Äôt Optional, They're Infectious: Bringing the same level of energy and enthusiasm as you would to watching your favorite TV show can make OKR check-in meetings more engaging and enjoyable for all participants.\n\"\nüé¢ Embrace the Roller Coaster of Confidence Scores: \"Static confidence scores are an indicator of a bigger problem, and not just a result of a flawed OKR process.\" This issue is often related to the company's mindset and culture, as teams need to feel empowered to take risks, experiment, and adapt based on new information.\n\"\nüöß Don‚Äôt Fear Missing a Key Result, It's a Goldmine of Insight: \"Missing a key result is not necessarily a bad thing.\" It is more about learning and generating insights that you can capitalize on, whether it's over the next week or the next quarter when you do the reflection.\n\"\nüåü Stewardship isn‚Äôt Just Important, It's Essential: \"Quality stewardship is crucial and should be prioritized.\" The OKR process relies heavily on stewards reporting accurate, reliable, and timely information to ensure good decision-making and progress towards objectives.\n\"\nüé© Pull Valuable Insights Out of Low Confidence Scores: \"Having a low confidence score can actually be beneficial.\" A significant drop in confidence scores can indicate that the team has uncovered new and valuable information that can be used to make better decisions moving forward.\n\"\nüéâ Turn Meetings into Brainstorm Parties: \"The OKR check-in meetings should be dynamic and engaging, with new information driving creative conversations and problem-solving.\" By ensuring these meetings focus on sense-making and planning, as well as sharing rich information through confidence scores and updates, the meetings become more valuable and enjoyable for attendees.\n\"\nüîÑ Consistency in Rituals Is Your Lifeline: Skipping weekly sync meetings can lead to a rapid deterioration of the OKR process, emphasizing the importance of maintaining a reliable ritual and consistent format across meetings.\n\"\n\"Watch the full talk: https://lnkd.in/geb9T5At",
