    "id": "post-2023-05-09-7061673364003696641",
    "title": "Last week, I spoke with entrepreneur & fellow AI enthusiast Jono Ma...",
    "date": "2023-05-09",
    "content": "Last week, I spoke with entrepreneur & fellow AI enthusiast Jono Matusky about how we've been using AI as a tool for exploration and discovery.\"\n\"\nSpecifically, we talked about using large language models (LLMs) to uncover intersections and gaps in knowledge and how this new capability might impact fields like PR and marketing.\n\"\nIn short, a layperson can now use a tool like ChatGPT to traverse parts of the human knowledge graph previously only accessible to experts. Versus standard internet searches, LLMs enable near-instant synthesis and translation of raw information‚Äîa good starting point for exploration.\n\"\nOne of my favorite ways to do this is by using ChatGPT to simulate a panel discussion by researchers working at the frontiers of their field. By simply asking ChatGPT to \"simulate and facilitate an impassioned discussion between these credible experts on [a topic you've just started exploring]\", you can identify issues that haven't yet been resolved by experts, prioritize primary sources, and identify credible individuals for outreach.*\n\"\nIn other words, you can quickly find a \"dark spot on the map\" and step right into it...\n\"\nJono noted that this LLM capability could allow folks in the media to identify interesting opportunities‚Äîfinding gaps in current reporting or looking for overlap between their coverage beat and the trajectory of current events. \n\"\nGoing one step further, journalists could use tools built on LLMs to help identify leading experts who may be able to provide interesting insight for a story. And vice versa: experts could use the models to better understand how to translate their message to the general public and identify those journalists who might be interested in their viewpoint.\n\"\nLLMs can be instrumental in crafting story angles, personalizing storytelling to the reader, and identifying whitespaces for stories at the intersection of topics that are typically not covered together but might be worth bringing attention to.\n\"\nIt's probably not long before you could Newsprint to analyze current news coverage, cross reference it with top experts in various fields, and come up with a list of potential story ideas targeted at different types of news readers.\n\"\nWe view these possibilities as parts of a general trend catalyzed by LLMs: one of lower-cost, bespoke software specifically tailored to meet the needs of top experts and professionals, affording them unprecedented leverage and more attention to invest in higher-level thinking and creative work.\n\"\n*Beware! Users should still expect LLM output to be made up (\"hallucinated\") about 20% of the time. Don‚Äôt use the ‚Äúresearchers‚Äô‚Äù names nor what they say during the debate w/o checking sources.\n\"\nThat said, we expect knowledge across the board‚Äîespecially executives, marketers, and PR professionals‚Äîto start integrating AI into their daily routines at an accelerating pace in 2023.\n\"\nWhat do you think about using LLMs to explore \"dark spots on the map\"?\n\"\n\"Add a comment with your thoughts!",
    "excerpt": "Last week, I spoke with entrepreneur & fellow AI enthusiast Jono Matusky about how we've been using AI as a tool for exploration and discovery.\" \"\"...",
