    "content": "Are you a no-code user who wants to pull their hair out when your pipelines break for mysterious reasons AND YOU CAN'T EVEN FIGURE OUT WHERE TO LOOK FOR THE BUG? ü§¨\"\n\"\nI just had a great conversation with another indie consultant, üöÄ Ambroise, who lives in France and helps early-stage startups around the world build tech and streamline processes with no-code tools.\n\"\nI asked him what insights or tips he had for no-code noobs like me (and other MBAs with product ideas but not the coding expertise) who want to use tools like Airtable to prototype ideas and even get them into stakeholders' hands.\n\"\nHe said that it's super important to make your documentation and variable naming conventions clear. If you don't, you pay for it in the long run.\n\"\nNo code pipelines break all the time. They're brittle, so a modicum of discipline goes a long way.\n\"\nBut, to someone who just wants to build quickly that sounds a lot like, \"eat your broccolli\": You know should do it, but you really don't want to.\n\"\nHe suggested instead using tools like nScale to help you get your arms around your massive tangle of no code pipelines.\n\"\nHe's even coded a custom tool that allows you to find exactly the variable you want across all of the different no code tools and pipelines that fit together to give you (or your boss or your client) the result that you want.\n\"\nSo, if you're a no-code user looking for insights and tips to streamline your workflow (and find those hidden variables causing you problems), consider sending him a DM to find out more: üöÄ Ambroise Dhenain\n\"\n\"#nocode #startup #streamline #work",
