    "title": "Setting good key results is essential to successful Objectives and ...",
    "date": "2022-12-22",
    "content": "Setting good key results is essential to successful Objectives and Key Results (OKRs).\"\n\"\nPreviously, I've written about what makes for a good objective.\n\"\nKnowing what criteria to look for when creating key results will help you craft a unified OKR, and help achieve the results you want.\n\"\nThose six criteria are \"quantitative,\" \"concrete,\" \"information efficient,\" \"coherent,\" \"stewarded,\" and \"exclusive.\n\"\nQuantitative: Each key result should be measurable. This means having a metric or a line in the sand that is binary, in that it is either achieved or not at the end of the quarter.\n\"\nConcrete: Make sure the key result is specific enough that everyone agrees on the definition. The key result should be measurable right when it's set‚Äînot in the future. If the result can‚Äôt be measured right away, opt for a proxy or imperfect approximation of the result. You can test this criterion by asking execs to pull the metric's value RIGHT NOW, and if they get the same numbers, it's a concrete measure.\n\"\nInformation Efficient: Each key result should provide information that the other two key results don‚Äôt. This doesn't mean \"uncorrelated\" per se. It can be satisfied by selecting one vital outcome and one quality input (which may be correlated in space, but not time‚Äîi.e., leading vs. lagging indicators). If the outcome takes a long time to achieve, the quality input will help the team focus on pulling proximal, reliable levers.¬†\n\"\nCoherent: All key results should fit together into a unified whole, both with each other and the objective. This can be tested by asking yourself whether achieving all the key results will also result in achieving the objective.¬†\n\"\nStewarded: Each key result should have a steward. This person is responsible for having access to the right information to know the odds of end-of-quarter KR success at any given time. While their confidence score should be gut-driven, it should be informed by accurate and useful information they have gathered over the course of the week, and is shared at the weekly LT sync meeting.\n\"\nExclusive: If you want extra constraints on the key result, you can make it more exclusive. For example, saying a key result should only pertain to a particular segment or geography will make it more focused and precise. This allows you to achieve additional depth (at the cost of breadth).\n\"\nBy understanding the criteria for setting good key results, you can craft objectives that lead to successful OKRs. These criteria will help you create unified goals and increase the probability of achieving the results you want.\n\"\n\"#okrs #strategy #management",
