    "title": "In my work with clients, no matter startup size or stage, I recomme...",
    "date": "2022-12-22",
    "content": "In my work with clients, no matter startup size or stage, I recommend they set a single objective and three key results (OKRs) for the entire company.\"\n\"\nWith everything riding on this unified objective, it's especially important that the executive team selects and articulates good and effective OKRs.\n\"\nLet's first define what an objective and key results are. An objective is a qualitative quarterly goal, while the key results are quantitative measures that fit back into the objective, allowing you to know clearly whether or not the overarching goal has been achieved.\n\"\nSo, what makes for a good objective?\n\"\n(I'll talk about key results in a subsequent post.)\n\"\nHere's a template: \"do X for Y by Z by A.\n\"\nStart with a verb, such as ‚Äúdo X‚Äù in the context of a particular stakeholder, \"Y.\" This is usually the customer. Then, optionally, you can add how you will do it if you want to further constrain the objective (\"Z\"); ‚Äúby A‚Äù refers to the time constraint, usually 12 weeks from when you set the OKRs.\n\"\nGood objectives should have six criteria: ambitious, aligned, prudent, strategic, qualitative, and charitable.¬†\n\"\nAmbitious objectives are inspiring (but achievable)‚Äîsomething that gets the whole team excited.\n\"\nAligned objectives are in line with the mission and vision of the company.\n\"\nBeing prudent means acknowledging capital constraints (do a financial model first!) and having a plausible narrative that connects the objective to the ultimate goal. While you can't know the future, you should at least be able to make a reasonable argument as to why taking this next step would logically connect to subsequent steps that ultimately allow you to achieve your mission and vision.\n\"\nObjectives should also be strategic. Focusing on the crux of the problem (to use Richard Rumelt's terminology) along a vertical hierarchy of choices along with the correct, limited range across a horizontal set of mutually exclusive choices are both important. The point here is that you're making a conscious and difficult choice to focus on one point of leverage (at the exclusion of others) that is likely to yield outsized progress and insights over the next quarter.\n\"\nObjectives should also be qualitative (no measure), allowing for  flexibility and room for personal projection (and, thus, ownership) by every member of the team.\n\"\nLastly, objectives should be charitable, meaning they should focus on the needs of the primary external stakeholder (e.g., the customer); the purpose of a corporation is to create value by solving problems using an information edge, and THEN capturing some of this value as profit returned to shareholders, hence the power of taking a charitable‚Äîand not self-oriented‚Äîapproach to goal-setting.\n\"\nBy keeping these criteria in mind when setting OKRs, you can make sure that your objectives and key results are effective in helping you achieve your goals.\n\"\nNext up: 6 criteria for good key results...keep an eye out for my next post!\n\"\n\"#OKRs #management #strategy",
