    "id": "post-2022-12-19-7010752137718550528",
    "title": "Objectives and key results (OKRs) help businesses and teams stay fo...",
    "date": "2022-12-19",
    "content": "Objectives and key results (OKRs) help businesses and teams stay focused on their goals and measure progress towards those goals. When executed properly, OKRs can lead to outsized results and help businesses and teams reach their full potential. It‚Äôs no wonder that they‚Äôre gaining popularity amongst executives and teams around the world.\"\n\"\nIn my recent presentation to the Chief of Staff Network (thanks, Rahul Desai and David Nebinski for hosting!), I outlined the three essential steps for successfully implementing OKRs. The first step is to set OKRs. This involves an executive workshop of around five hours, preceded by preparatory trust-building and information gathering activities. At the end of the workshop, you should have one objective and three key results. These should be ambitious enough that there is a 50/50 chance of achieving them in a quarter. Each key result should also have a steward who is accountable for knowing the odds of success of achieving that key result.\n\"\nThe second step is to sync weekly, which involves a meeting of around an hour to surface new information, make plans to exploit that information towards the end of outsized progress. The third step is to reflect quarterly, which is when we \"uncover the truth,\" mine insights, and shape company culture.\n\"\nThe pitfalls to avoid when setting and tracking OKRs include: having more than one objective and three key results; sharing OKRs with external stakeholders (who will inevitably mistake a tool for learning for committed targets); skipping weekly check-ins; and allowing the weekly syncs to descend into status update hell.\n\"\nFor teams of 300 people or less, weekly syncs are the key to success. This is when the key stakeholders come together to discuss progress on the key results and assign a confidence score of how likely they are to be achieved. This is also the time to identify any heroic narratives, i.e. a team member who went above and beyond expectations to achieve a key result.\n\"\nFinally, communication is key in this process. This can include recording and transcribing meetings, conducting anonymous surveys, and using a technique called \"backbriefing,\" where the strategic intent is communicated to everyone on the team.\n\"\n\"Overall, setting and tracking OKRs is essential to achieving business objectives, and it‚Äôs important to have an effective system in place to ensure that teams stay on track and progress is monitored effectively and efficiently. If you're looking to implement OKRs into your business and don't know where to start, sign up for a free consultation (https://gsdat.work) to get tailored advice on how to make sure you're doing it right ‚Äî and join the Chief of Staff Network!",
