    "title": "Why is it absolutely critical that you protect your attention durin...",
    "date": "2022-12-13",
    "content": "Why is it absolutely critical that you protect your attention during the workday?\"\n\"\nWell, if you care about long-term success, producing quality work, and getting to the root of a given problem, then you might want to go out of your way to vanquish distractions...\n\"\nLet's use Plato's \"Pyramid of Thought\" to understand why this is the case.\n\"\nAbout 2,400 years ago, Greek philosopher Plato came up with a framework for understanding the levels of human thought. They are (from lowest to highest):\n\"\n1. \"Eikasia,\" roughly our immediate emotion responses to raw inputs from our immediate environment;\n2. \"Pistis,\" simple heuristics and \"just-so\" stories that use to quickly make sense of a stream of raw input;\n3. \"Dianoia,\" discursive critical thinking, through which we consider multiple interpretations and use reason; and\n4. \"Noesis,\" a deep, generalizable understanding that's almost like catching a glimpse of the source code of reality.\n\"\nThe thing is, moving up each level of the pyramid requires focus and unbroken periods of concentrated attention ‚Äî¬†so, if you're constantly distracted, moving from one external input to another, you'll inevitably get stuck at the lower levels. And if you stay stuck, then you'll never be able to get at the root of whatever it is you're trying to accomplish.\n\"\nHow does this play out in the digital age?\n\"\nLet's take social media‚ÄîTwitter to be very specific‚Äîas an example:\n\"\nTweets are incredibly short, and because the algorithm is optimized for engagement, the tweets that are mostly likely to draw your attention (in other words, the most potent external stimuli at the level of eikasia) end up at the top of your feed.\n\"\nIt's no wonder Twitter threads get adversarial and stay so emotionally heated! The medium is simply not conducive to moving past (at best) pistis ... everyone's simple heuristics/worldviews are further simplified and reinforced; nuance, the thing that emerges at the stage of dianoia, is lost.\n\"\nWhile perhaps less extreme, the same principle holds true for every other digital channel: from Slack to email inboxes to LinkedIn posts :)\n\"\nKnowledge work is ultimately about developing a practical understanding of the world that can be used to help people achieve their goals more effectively and efficiently.\n\"\nTrue understanding (those precious \"a-ha\" moments) requires movement up (and then back down) Plato's Pyramid.\n\"\nWhat does this mean in practice?\n\"\nWell, in an age of infinite digital breadth, it's more important than ever to develop a disciplined approach to achieving depth: e.g., attenuating digital distractions, batching your inboxes, and carving out ample time to contemplate.\n\"\nReady to go deeper on a daily basis?\n\"\nAdd your tips for staying focused and \"thinking better\" in the comments!\n\"\n\"#digital #work #socialmedia #focus #philosophy #productivity",
