    "id": "post-2022-12-09-7006999701883355137",
    "title": "When you're managing a remote team, running effective cross-functio...",
    "date": "2022-12-09",
    "content": "When you're managing a remote team, running effective cross-functional team meetings‚Äîespecially with execs‚Äîis absolutely critical.\"\n\"\nA 2-hour meeting with 5 executives during deep work hours costs the company ~$2,500!\n\"\nYou wouldn't waste thousands of dollars of cash...so, why not hold meetings to the same high standards?\n\"\nPut that invaluable group attention to work with the following best practices:\n\"\n1. Articulate clear outcomes and outputs before creating an agenda. Your agenda should be a function of your goal, not the other way around.\n2. Block 2 hours for all remote meetings. I know this sounds crazy, but outsized progress requires periods of unbroken focus, and we're able to achieve our deepest levels of focus in 90-minute \"ultradian cycles.\" If you can achieve the same outcome via other channels (e.g., asynchronous comments on a shared document), do that instead.\n3. Share meeting outcomes, outputs, and a time-boxed agenda in the invite. I wish Google Apps for Business could force users to do this before being able to invite anyone to a meeting...\n4. Spend the first 10 minutes reviewing the outcomes, outputs, sharing an \"up-front contract\" (UFC), setting ground rules, and sharing \"top-of-minds\" (TOMs). The UFC should give attendees the leeway to exit the meeting at any point if they feel it's not worth their attention. Ground rules should include filtering out all digital distractions. By verbalizing what's TOM (work or personal) for each attendee, that competing priority is neutralized.\n5. Hit record. Going forward (and thanks to AI), the organizations that commit to radical transparency by recording and sharing meetings by default will have a massive advantage over those that do not by radically decreasing the biggest cost drivers of management overhead: knowledge capture, management, and transfer.\n6. Spend 90 minutes in deep discussion w/ help from a multimedia tool like Miro.\n7. Spend 10m closing, ESPECIALLY getting real-time feedback via a \"fist-to-five\": ask attendees to put up a fist (complete waste of time) to five fingers (great use of time) and ask outliers why they didn't rate it lower OR what it would take to rate higher. This gut-driven information is GOLD. Use those insights to continuously improve meetings and surface insights that would otherwise be left unsaid.\n8. Leave 10m of buffer so attendees can break and prepare for their next engagement.\n9. Publish the recording, a transcript (that any team member can add comments to for async discussion of pertinent topics), and AI-generated summary (h/t Scribbl) to a public Slack/Teams channel.\n\"\nIf you stick to these, I GUARANTEE you'll start getting better results. And as leaders are expected to deliver better outcomes with leaner teams, human capital‚Äìefficient results matter more than ever.\n\"\nAny other remote team meeting tips?\n\"\nAdd one in the comments below! üëá\n\"\n\"#management #remoteworking #AI #meetings #digital",
