    "id": "post-2022-11-23-7001211751656472576",
    "title": "Let's talk about \"status update hell\": what it is, why you're there...",
    "date": "2022-11-23",
    "content": "Let's talk about \"status update hell\": what it is, why you're there, and how to get out...\"\n\"\nIt's a Tuesday morning at 10am. You chug a cup of coffee and hop on Zoom for the recurring weekly \"team sync\" meeting. It's supposed to go for 60 minutes but usually lasts 90. There are 9 other attendees. Their eyes track from left-to-right for most of the meeting; they are reading email and scanning Slack threads while speakers rattle off a laundry list of last week's to-do's. Someone screen shares a project tracker. The status flags are green. There are no questions‚Äîonly statements. Your gut tells you that the company is not on the right track. But there's no cell in the status spreadsheet for your \"gut feeling,\" so you stay quiet.\n\"\nI have bad news: you are in the 8th circle of status update hell.\n\"\nWe all know that regular team syncs are critical‚Äîespecially for remote teams‚Äîand, yet, these meetings too often devolve into rote performances of minimal substance. (And they cost $$$, especially at the exec level.)\n\"\nThis is usually because there's not a unified, medium‚Äìlong-term objective anchoring the discussion. When that common end is unclear, attendees will understandably revert to sharing information relevant to their own personal objectives, which may or may not be aligned with those of the broader team, let alone the company.\n\"\nThe good news is that there's a way out‚Äîall you need to do is make a few simple tweaks*:\n\"\n1. Anchor the entire meeting with a common, unified goal, e.g., 1 objective & 3 key results.\n2. Assign a \"steward\" for each key result. This person is responsible for sharing a single confidence score at the beginning of each meeting (0‚Äì100%) that the result will be achieved by the end of the quarter. Note that the stewards are not responsible for achieving the results, only acting as \"nerve centers\" that can aggregate the relevant information each week into gut-driven scores.\n3. Rank the key results according to the gap between last week's confidence score and this week's. A gap means something changed, which means there are insights to be mined, shared, and possibly exploited in the coming week.\n4. Ask the group two sequential questions: \"Why the change?\" and \"What might we do this week to turn X% into 90%?\n\"\nIn adopting this meeting format, you've implemented a filtering mechanism that selects for vital information‚Äîinformation that moves the team closer to its long-term goal.\n\"\nThis means that there will be meetings where only a single key result is discussed. This is not only OK, but a desirable outcome‚Äîthe attendees' valuable attention will be invested in the cognitively taxing and high-leverage tasks of developing causal models to make sense of the changes and generating creative hypotheses that you can test in the week ahead.\n\"\nTo get out of status update hell, maintain focus on what's vital!\n\"\n\"*\"simple, but difficult\" as Christina Wodtke says in \"Radical Focus,\" the BEST book on #OKRs and the source of the confidence score approach",
