    "id": "post-2022-11-21-7000577961951133698",
    "title": "Let's talk about insights, innovation, and the (in)famous Rumsfeld ...",
    "date": "2022-11-21",
    "content": "Let's talk about insights, innovation, and the (in)famous Rumsfeld Matrix...\"\n\"\nWhen you make time for reflection‚Äîsay, at a team retrospective or quarterly OKR review‚Äîit's important to take stock of not only what you've learned but how you learned it.\n\"\nThe most successful entrepreneurs and business leaders are the ones who can learn the fastest. BUT there's no one-size-fits-all approach to learning. \"How\" you learn is a function of \"where\" you are.\n\"\nAs researchers Dave Snowden and Simon Wardley have pointed out, an approach to problem-solving and management that works great in one problem space or product development stage may fail or be counterproductive at another. For example, an early stage startup team probably shouldn't be using Six Sigma.\n\"\nOne way of thinking about \"where\" you are is to use a mental model derived from Donald Rumsfeld's 2002 statement, \"there are known knowns...\n\"\nImagine a 2x2 with two axes that run from unknown to known.\n\"\nTo learn is to move information into the \"known known\" quadrant from all others. But how you do that depends on the starting quadrant.\n\"\nThe \"unknown unknown\" is the frontier. It's dangerous. Operating there is risky, but also rewarding. When you set a good quarterly goal, you'll end up spending at least some time here‚Äîand whatever insights you gain can be transformed into an information edge and/or competitive advantage.\n\"\nWhen you known you don't know something you can do one of two things: either run experiments to tease out causal relationships or consult experts who know the things you know you don't.\n\"\nSometimes, you discover insights in the rather odd \"unknown known\" quadrant. These are the superpowers your team didn't know they had‚Äîan information edge that you weren't leveraging before. Individual strength/personality assessments can be great sources of these: Gallup StrengthsFinder, Luke Burgis's MCODE, or Crystal Knows.\n\"\nOnce you've moved information into the \"known known\" quadrant, you can \"compress\" it into a new technology, product, or process that makes it easy for others to use it.\n\"\nKnown knowns\" are fleeting (hence the infamous nature of the Rumsfeld quote), and your routinized model will need to be fixed, updated, or scrapped‚Äîit all depends on whether info gained from additional experimentation and expert consultation can account for the anomaly.\n\"\nOther times, a \"known known\" melds with the organizational culture in such a deep way that it can't really be codified and so becomes an \"unknown known.\" Oddly enough, this becomes a source of market power (Hamilton Helmer's \"process power\") because no single person can replicate it elsewhere.\n\"\nBy taking periodic snapshots of the evolving landscape of things you know, things you don't, and everything in between, entrepreneurs & innovators make better decisions and develop sound strategy with a Socratic ethos: \"I know that I know nothing.\n\"\n\"#innovation #learning #management #strategy #OKRs",
