    "title": "When it comes to setting good OKRs each quarter, executives have to...",
    "date": "2022-11-03",
    "content": "When it comes to setting good OKRs each quarter, executives have to perform a delicate balance act between breadth and depth.\"\n\"\nOn one hand, the more precise you can be with your objective and key results (e.g., choosing a single customer segment, restricting the methods by which you can achieve your desired outcomes), the further you can progress toward your longer-term objectives.\n\"\nHowever, gains from precision are contingent upon a real strategic wedge. In other words, if you're not darn sure that the restricted scope of your team's definition of quarterly success (and, thus, the scope of their activities) will yield outsized results, then you run the risk of being too parochial.\n\"\nAt best, you'll overshoot your right-sized strategic next step‚Äîand, at worst, you'll veer WAY off course.\n\"\nOn the other hand, if you give yourself more breadth, you've limited the magnitude of progress you can achieve in the forthcoming period. Team members may pursue incompatible opportunities, become untethered from one another at strategic forks in the road, and ultimately waste resources.\n\"\nThe bad news is that there's no easy way whether to optimize for breadth or depth. It really depends on where you are in your team's journey.\n\"\nThe good news is that by running effective OKR review meetings every quarter, you can unearth invaluable insights that help you make the right decisions when setting OKRs for the coming quarters‚Äîincluding whether to prioritize breadth or depth in the months ahead.\n\"\nHave you ever worked on a team that set quarterly (or monthly or yearly) goals with unwavering confidence, only to realize a few weeks in that they were completely wrong...\n\"\nHow did you handle it?\n\"\n\"#okr #goalsetting #strategy #management",
