    "date": "2022-11-02",
    "content": "Isn't \"quiet quitting\" just...setting healthy boundaries?\"\n\"\nI'd rather work with colleagues (and manage directs) who are well-rested and can devote their full attention to their jobs during the workday.\n\"\nAllowing, let alone encouraging, an \"always on\" culture is unhealthy and ultimately counterproductive.\n\"\nIf someone isn't performing, that's one thing‚Äîbut expecting someone to sacrifice the valuable attention they should be investing in their personal relationships and family community/obligations is something else entirely.\n\"\nBecause of the technology and design \"best practices\" that were developed to support the growth of the consumer internet economy, which is ultimately fueled by advertising spend (which, in turn, is only possible in a consumer economy with inexpensive credit), we've come to expect each other to prioritize short-term responsiveness over longer-term value creation.\n\"\nWhile immediately responding to an email at 9pm might give the sender a quick surge of dopamine, it is unlikely a meaningful contribution to your company's strategic objectives.\n\"\nAnd it comes at a cost‚Äîcompulsively checking your email at 9pm comes at the cost of higher-quality attention to your immediate environment AND your most important, productive work the next morning.\n\"\nOr maybe I'm just an entitled Millennial who doesn't get it üòâ\n\"\n\"#work #genz #quietquitting",
