    "id": "post-2022-11-01-6993257407254560768",
    "title": "Life is but a series of marshmallow tests",
    "date": "2022-11-01",
    "content": "Life is but a series of marshmallow tests.\"\n\"\nAnd we are awash in a sea of digital marshmallows...\n\"\nMany years ago, I came to the realization that delayed gratification was the key to happiness.\n\"\nWith each temptation that I resisted, I found myself becoming more calm, more focused, and more confident. It became easier to make good decisions, discern opportunities from distractions, and choose well. I have never since regretted taking a long-term perspective.\n\"\nIn the 90s, the average American found herself tempted by marshmallows made of atoms: As a college undergrad, for example, you could choose between studying for a final or drinking on frat row. Once you committed to holing yourself up in the library, the siren song of a night wasted (no pun intended) went silent. Your friends wouldn't even know where you were, let alone how to bother you.\n\"\nAs the ancients knew, it's never been easy for humans to make good decisions, BUT in the pre-digital world it was harder to make bad ones.\n\"\nOur choices were limited by local constraints in time and space; we were necessarily discerning. Every step you took required time, energy, and‚Äîif, say, you wanted to call a cab to head to that frat party‚Äîphysical cash.\n\"\nBut now, making bad decisions is easier than ever.\n\"\nYou can order booze and burritos directly to your apartment. You can find charismatic bloggers and YouTube creators that reinforce your imprudent beliefs, gain your trust, and hawk their wares. You can access cheap credit with frictionless options to \"buy now and pay later\" at checkout. You can stream any particular selection of engaging (and, soon, immersive) digital content directly into your eyes and ears, substituting socialization, intimacy, and meaning with hyper-engineered simulations.\n\"\nAlthough these bad choices are somewhat limited to the world of bits, thereby mitigating catastrophic consequences, they are insidious and should carefully be avoided precisely for the same reason. Short-term errors compound, and without sufficient pain, there's no correction through learning.\n\"\nOn one hand, if you substitute an evening out for one of solitude, game-controller in hand, you don't run the risk of getting hit by a drunk driver.\n\"\nOn the other hand, while a Drizly-enhanced evening of Fortnite might leave you \"only\" with a hangover and a twang of embarrassment after purchasing a lavish digital item, that same activity (unlike the night out) is always at hand‚Äîliterally a few button-pushes and swipes away.\n\"\nFeeling bored at \"work\" (you work at home)? Unhappy with the state of your social life? Feeling particularly rattled by warzone footage you came across on Twitter?\n\"\nJust eat a marshmallow.\n\"\nBecause we now have the ability to work, play, and socialize through digital media, it's easy drown in short-term satisfaction by scarfing down handfuls of mini-marshmallows throughout the day.\n\"\nThe next time you're tempted by a digital marshmallow, don't eat it.\n\"\n\"Your future self will thank you for it.",
