    "id": "post-2022-10-31-6992983732429144064",
    "title": "Almost a year ago, I did my first serious digital detox",
    "date": "2022-10-31",
    "content": "Almost a year ago, I did my first serious digital detox.\"\n\"\nIt was EXCRUCIATING.\n\"\nLittle by little‚Äîand especially in the beginning months of the pandemic‚Äîmy various digital habits (a little Twitter here, some extra email there) had crept up on me until I found myself almost entirely plugged into the Matrix.\n\"\nAfter working all day in the annals of Slack, Airtable, and Google Meet, I'd bounce between Clubhouse rooms and kitchen conversations with my in-laws, one bluetooth earbud in, while keeping an eye on cryptocurrency prices and responding to 10pm Slack threads from coworkers in France.\n\"\nI was always-on, always hyped, ready to absorb and regurgitate the latest information I'd picked from some corner of the internet, pouring energy into ongoing threads with strangers on topics as wide-ranging as healthcare economics, Deleuzian philosophy, and the history of western esoteric traditions.\n\"\nBut I started to sense that it was all too much‚Äîthat between the podcast episodes I'd been pumping into my brain during grocery runs, crowding out shopping list items that I struggled to remember, and the fact that I'd begun to find it challenging to watch an entire documentary with my fianc√©e without glancing at my phone, I needed to dial things back.\n\"\nSo I did. Drastically.\n\"\nI shut off my laptop and phone strictly between the hours of 8pm and 8am every day. I unplugged completely on Sundays. I turned all of my screens to greyscale and deleted all social media apps (and then logged out of the web versions). I made the switch to Superhuman, kept my phone out of the bedroom, and waited to check my inbox (i.e., email, Discord, Slack, Signal, WhatsApp, Telegram, Facebook Messenger) until 1pm every day.\n\"\nI eschewed podcasts and music during workouts. I even averted my eyes from cable news when I caught glimpses of it at the gym and in the kitchen.\n\"\nI spent a growing amount of time alone with my thoughts. And, man, was it painful (at first).\n\"\nI'd forgotten what it was like to be bored, a feeling of which I had vague memories: waiting for my parents to pick me up from elementary school, making my way through heats at a weekend swim meet, afternoons at the local library spent searching through book indices on a quest for information that I could write on paper notecards and turn into a research paper on Nepal.\n\"\nAfter about 10 tough days, I started noticing changes...\n\"\nTasks that I previously had zero interest in doing‚Äîfrom unloading the dishwasher to troubleshooting an issue with our home internet connection‚Äîsuddenly became quite interesting.\n\"\nThose local problems that needed my attention were no longer competing with digital distractions, and I found myself actually ENJOYING doing chores around the house.\n\"\nNow, when I read or listen or watch, I slow down and absorb information, rather than inhale it. My sleep is immaculate. The quality of my thinking (and work product) is MUCH higher.\n\"\nI'm doing less, but better.\n\"\n\"Have you ever tried a digital detox? How did it go?",
