    "id": "post-2022-10-28-6991790164880588800",
    "title": "‚ÄúYou are what you eat",
    "date": "2022-10-28",
    "content": "‚ÄúYou are what you eat.‚Äù\"\n\"\nDietary habits matter‚Äî not just in the world of atoms, but also in the world of bits.\n\"\nConsumer information technology products have, unfortunately, evolved to exploit our instincts.\n\"\nWe wanted flying cars, but got 140 characters‚Äîand after a decade of capital being plowed into the attention economy, tweets have begun to resemble digital Doritos, with hyper-engineered ‚Äúflavor profiles‚Äù that hijack our informational taste buds.\n\"\nToo many of us are sustaining ourselves on the digital equivalent of Fritos and Mountain Dew.\n\"\nAnd then there are the ‚Äúwork apps,‚Äù more informational junk food with limited nutritional content but painted with a veneer of legitimacy that makes it easier for the modern knowledge worker to rationalize his or her compulsive email or Slack habit.\n\"\nLike candy bars marketed as protein bars, most enterprise ‚Äúproductivity‚Äù software isn‚Äôt going to yield the benefits you were promised. But, in the short run, it sure does taste good.\n\"\nFortunately, food manufacturers are compelled to share nutrition facts and most phone and computer manufacturers include native screen time analytics reporting features.\n\"\nIf you‚Äôre reading this on an iPhone or Mac, go into your screen time report for last week and look at the total amount of time you spent in front of your devices. (This, of course, does not include the attention given to TV-based media like Netflix, video games, or cable news.)\n\"\nWhat percentage of the ~100 waking hours you have per week did you spend in front of a screen? And how does that make you feel?\n\"\nNow, scroll down to look at where those hours were spent. Just as not all calories are the same, not all screen time hours are the same. There is the matter of quality.\n\"\nGiven your values, your obligations to your employer, your family, your community, and yourself, are you thankful for spending the hours that you did on each one of those apps? Or do you have any regrets?\n\"\nThis ‚Äúexamination of digital conscience‚Äù is unconfortable, but a crucial habit to develop if you want to thrive in the 21st century.\n\"\nWith the advent of the next generation of media at the intersection of VR, AI, and crypto, the ‚Äúdigital drugs‚Äù will only get stronger.\n\"\nNow is the time to start strengthening your mind armor and treating your attention as an investment good, not a consumption good.\n\"\nOn a scale of 1-5 how satisfied are you with what you see in your screen time report? And what can you do this week to move it up a point by the next time you check?\n\"\nShare in the comments below üëá\n\"\n\" #productivity #analytics #work",
